{In this lecture we will discuss: 1. Typical endgame structures from various
branches of the London system 2. Endgames from theoretical opening variations
in the London system (with early queen exchange) White typically does not want
to trade queens because of: 1. losing attacking potential 2. no typical space
advantage for White – Black usually have a comfortable endgame Typical
features of the London system endgames: 1. Long pawn chains (on both sides)
and closed centre 2. Importance of pawn play and pawn breaks (piece play is
less crucial)} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 d5 3. e3 c5 4. c3 ({One of the modern move
orders is} 4. Nd2 Nc6 5. Ngf3 Qb6 6. dxc5 Qxb2 7. Rb1 $13) 4... Nc6 5. Nf3 {
This is the old London system move order, which is not considered the best for
White these days.} (5. Nd2 {is more accurate for White as after} Qb6 6. Qb3 c4
7. Qc2 {[%cal Bc8f5] Black cannot go Bf5 as in the old main line.}) 5... Qb6 $1
6. Qb3 c4 7. Qxb6 {The arising endgame is not considered to be so good for
White any more.} ({The main alternative} 7. Qc2 Bf5 8. Qc1 {will be discussed
in Game 2.}) 7... axb6 {[%cal Bb6b5,Bb5b4] opening of the a-file is in Black's
favour, he has a simple plan to push the b-pawn(s).} 8. Na3 {[#] This is the
only way White can prevent this plan, while also threatening to jump to b5.
What is the best move for Black now?} e5 $6 {looks tempting, but it is
actually suspicious.} (8... Bf5 $1 {developing the bishop to the best diagonal
and not fearing any ghosts on the queenside.} 9. Nh4 ({In the event of} 9. Bc7
e6 (9... Rxa3 $5 10. bxa3 e6 $44 {is also an option}) 10. Nb5 Kd7 11. Bxb6 Ra6
12. Bc7 Bc2 $1 {[%csl Bc7,Bb5][%cal Bc2a4] is the key, when white pieces on
the queenside become vulnerable.}) (9. Nb5 Ra5 10. a4 e6 11. Bc7 Bc2 $1 {
is similar.}) 9... Bd7 10. Nf3 (10. Bc7 e5 11. Nc2 e4 12. f4 b5 $19 {0-1 (26)
Bochkarev,A (2302) -Smirnov,P (2626) Izhevsk 2014}) {Black can repeat the
moves with 10...Bf5, but he can also be more ambitious with} 10... Ra5 $5 $146
11. Bc7 Ne4 $1 {[%csl Bc3]} 12. Nb1 Bf5 13. Nbd2 (13. Nh4 Be6 14. f3 Nf6 $17)
13... Kd7 14. Bg3 {White should abandon the plan to win the b6-pawn after all.
Black has a more pleasant endgame after} b5 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 16. a3 e6 $15 {
We will discuss this type of endgame in Game 3: Vitiugov-Radjabov.}) ({Moves
like} 8... Ra5) ({and} 8... Na7 {are also playable, but 8...Bf5 seems to be
Black's best option.}) 9. Nb5 Ra5 10. Nc7+ Kd7 {It looks like the knight is
trapped, but White has a nice tactical idea:} 11. dxe5 $1 Nh5 12. Nxd5 Rxd5 13.
Bxc4 Nxf4 14. exf4 Rc5 15. Bxf7 $13 {Black won the knight but had to pay a
high price for it - 4 pawns. Moreover, these pawns are compact and strong, so
they can become a big asset for White in the endgame. While the position
remains unclear, White seems to have an easier game. Here is an example:} Be7
16. Nd4 Rf8 17. Be6+ Ke8 18. Bxc8 Nxd4 19. cxd4 Rxc8 20. g3 {White's pawn
chain is impressive. Interestingly, all 8 pawns are still on the board.} Bb4+
$2 ({The only way for Black was} 20... Rc2 21. h4 Rxb2 22. O-O $13) 21. Ke2 g5
(21... Rc2+ 22. Kf3 Rxb2 23. Rab1 $18) 22. Rac1 $1 Rxc1 23. Rxc1 gxf4 24. a3
Be7 25. Rc7 fxg3 26. hxg3 h5 27. Rxb7 h4 28. Rxb6 hxg3 29. fxg3 Bd8 30. Rb7 Rh8
31. Kf3 Rh1 32. Ke4 {1-0 Black resigns.} 1-0

