1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6 6. Qb3 c4 7. Qc2 {This way,
White avoids the endgame. Nevertheless, it is useful to see some typical
endgames that could arise in this line.} Bf5 8. Qc1 e6 (8... Nh5 $5 {is a
modern treatment, eliminating the strong bishop straight away.} 9. Bg3 e6 10.
Nbd2 Nxg3 11. hxg3 {[%cal Bb8g3] The upside of this exchange for Black, apart
from getting the bishop pair, is that h2-b8 diagonal is available for his
pieces now. The downside is that the knight is not on f6 any more, so White
can easily carry out e3-e4.} h6 12. Be2 Be7 13. Bd1 Qc7 14. Bc2 {[%csl Bf6]}
O-O 15. e4 dxe4 16. Nxe4 Rad8 17. Qf4 $5 {[%cal Bg3f4,Bh2g3] An interesting
way to reach the endgame. We will see this idea also in Game 6: Le Tuan-Riff.}
Qxf4 18. gxf4 b5 19. a3 f6 {preparing pawn breaks ...e5 and ...g5.} 20. O-O Rd5
21. Rfe1 g5 22. fxg5 hxg5 {[#] The critical position. How should White
continue?} 23. Re2 {Not a bad move,} ({but pawn breaks are crucial! The best
move was} 23. b3 $1 {preparing to open some files on the queenside and weaken
black pawns.} Na5 24. bxc4 (24. b4 $5 Nb3 $1 (24... Nc6 25. a4 $16) 25. Bxb3
cxb3 $132) 24... bxc4 (24... Nxc4 25. a4 a6 26. axb5 axb5 27. Bb3 $16) 25. Rab1
Bxa3 26. Nh2 $1 $14 {[%cal Gh2f1,Gf1e3]}) (23. a4 $6 b4 $15) (23. Nfd2 $5 {
preparing 23.a4, was another active option.} e5 24. a4 b4 25. Nxc4 exd4 $13)
23... g4 24. Nfd2 (24. Ne1 {looks more solid.} e5 25. Ng3 Bxc2 26. Nxc2) 24...
e5 $1 {Model play with pawns by Carlsen.} 25. dxe5 Nxe5 {Black got rid of the
backward e6-pawn and has opened the position in his favor.} 26. b3 $2 (26. a4
b4 27. b3 $1 $132) 26... Rfd8 27. Nf1 Bg6 28. bxc4 bxc4 29. Ne3 Rb5 $15 {
0-1 (58) Kamsky,G (2714)-Carlsen,M (2714) Moscow 2007}) 9. Nbd2 Qd8 {[%cal
Bb7b5]} 10. h3 h6 11. Be2 Be7 {This is the classical way to play this
variation.} (11... Bd6 {is inaccurate because of} 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. b3 b5 14.
a4) 12. O-O O-O 13. Bd1 {[%cal Bd1c2,Be3e4,Yb7b5] A typical maneuver to
prepare the e2-e4 break and trade opponent's stronger bishop. Meanwhile, Black
tries to make advances on the queenside:} b5 14. Bc2 Bxc2 (14... a5 $5 {
[%cal Re3e4] is, perhaps, more accurate. Black does not mind the exchange on
f5 as it helps him strengthen control over e4-square. A recent GM game
continued:} 15. Ne5 (15. Bxf5 exf5) (15. Re1 {is another option to prepare
e3-e4, although after} b4 16. e4 dxe4 17. Nxe4 Nd5 {Black has a nice position.}
) 15... Nxe5 16. Bxe5 Nd7 17. Bxf5 exf5 18. Bh2 Nb6 (18... Nf6 $5 {[%csl Ye4]})
19. Qc2 g6 20. f3 Bd6 ({A more promising plan might have been} 20... b4 $5 21.
e4 Qd7 $1 {using the fact that the endgame after 22.exf5 Qxf5 is just bad for
White.} 22. Rae1 (22. exf5 $2 Qxf5 23. Qxf5 gxf5 $19 {[%csl Bc3,Bb2]}) 22...
Rfe8 23. Re2 Bg5 $15) 21. e4 Bxh2+ 22. Kxh2 f4 23. e5 Qg5 24. Rae1 Rae8 $13 {
1-0 (84) Sadhwani,R (2545)-Nagy,G (2495) Lichess.org INT 2021}) 15. Qxc2 Bd6 {
Parligras' strategy in this game was apparently to exchange all pieces, but we
will see how that failed.} ({Instead, Black should create queenside
counterplay at any possible opportunity, for example:} 15... b4 16. e4 a5 $132
{[%csl Ba5][%cal Ba5a3]}) 16. Bxd6 Qxd6 17. e4 dxe4 18. Nxe4 Nxe4 19. Qxe4 Qd5
$6 ({Again, it was better to attack the c3-pawn with} 19... Ne7 20. Ne5 Rac8
21. Rfe1 Nd5 22. a3 a5 $132 {[%cal Gb5b4]}) 20. Qxd5 exd5 21. Ne5 $1 Nxe5 22.
dxe5 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gf2f4] Suddenly, White has a slight initiative in a
drawish endgame. But Black has to be more careful now.} f6 23. Rad1 Rad8 24.
Rfe1 Kf7 $6 (24... Rfe8 25. exf6 Rxe1+ 26. Rxe1 gxf6 27. Re7 d4 28. cxd4 Rxd4
29. Rxa7 Rd1+ 30. Kh2 Rd2 $11) 25. exf6 gxf6 {This seems unnecessarily
weakening.} (25... Kxf6 26. f4 $14) 26. Kf1 $14 Rfe8 27. Rxe8 Kxe8 28. Ke2 Ke7
29. Rd4 $1 {[%csl Rf6,Rh6] [#] White starts exploiting opponent's weaknesses.
Yet, the game is still well within the drawing margin. How should Black
continue?} Ke6 ({Active play is the best policy in rook endgames!} 29... a5 $1
$132 30. Rh4 b4 31. Rxh6 Rb8 32. Ke3 a4 $1 33. a3 bxa3 34. bxa3 Rb3 35. Kd4
Rxa3 36. g4 Ra2 37. Kxd5 Rd2+ 38. Kxc4 Rxf2 {and Black will get a drawn 2 vs 1
rook endgame}) ({Passive defenses like} 29... Kf7 30. Rh4 Kg6) ({and} 29... f5
30. Rh4 Rd6 {[%csl Be7,Bf5][%cal Be2f3,Bf3f4] should also work for Black.}) 30.
Rh4 Rg8 $2 {Too passive. Black is losing now.} (30... b4 {was begging to be
played.}) 31. g4 Rh8 32. Rh5 a5 33. Ke3 Kd6 34. Kd4 $18 Kc6 35. Rxd5 Re8 36.
Rc5+ Kb6 37. Rf5 Re2 38. Rxf6+ Kb7 39. b3 Rxa2 40. bxc4 b4 41. cxb4 axb4 42.
Kc5 b3 43. Rb6+ Kc7 44. Rxb3 Rxf2 45. Ra3 h5 46. Ra7+ Kb8 47. Rh7 hxg4 48. hxg4
Rg2 49. Rg7 Kc8 50. g5 Rg4 51. g6 {1-0 Black resigns.} 1-0

