1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 {The game started as a Trompowsky, but a typical London
System structure was reached very soon.} d5 3. e3 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nd2 Qb6 6.
Qb3 e6 7. Ngf3 Be7 8. Qxb6 {Opening of the a-file is usually in Black's favour.
} (8. Be2 {was more flexible, at least.}) 8... axb6 9. a3 Bd7 10. Be2 h6 11.
Bf4 O-O 12. h3 {Eventually, players have reached a London-system type of
position.} Rfc8 13. O-O Be8 14. Ne5 Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Bc6 16. Rfc1 {[#] Which plan
would you suggest for Black here?} Nd7 17. Bg3 b5 $1 {[%csl Bb2][%cal Gd7b6,
Gb6a4] preparing to play on the queenside.} (17... f6 $5 18. Nf3 Kf7 {is a
reasonable alternative.}) 18. Nf3 (18. dxc5 Nxc5 {[%cal Bc5a4,Ba4b6,Bb6c4,
Be6e5,Bd4c5,Bf7f6] seems to compromise Black's pawn structure, leaving double
and isolated pawns on the b-file, but it surrenders the centre. At the same
time, Black can neutralize the weakness of b5-pawn with a manoeuvre
Nc5-a4-b6-c4.}) 18... c4 19. Bd1 (19. Ne5 Nb6) 19... Nb6 20. Nd2 Ra6 21. Rab1
Rca8 22. Bc2 Na4 {[%csl Bb2,Ba3,Bc3] Black is ready to sacrifice a piece on
one of the critical squares, so White has no choice but to eliminate the
dangerous knight.} 23. Bxa4 (23. Re1 Nxc3 $1 24. bxc3 Rxa3 $19) 23... bxa4 {
[%csl Rb2][%cal Ga6b6] Now, the b2-pawn can be attacked via the b-file.} 24. f3
f6 {[%cal Gc6e8,Ge8g6] Planning to improve the idle bishop on c6.} ({The
straightforward attack on the b-file} 24... Rb6 25. Re1 Rb5 26. e4 Ra6 27. Re2
Rab6 {does not quite work because of} 28. Bc7) (24... h5 $5 {might have been a
useful inclusion.} 25. h4 (25. Re1 h4 26. Bh2 f6) 25... f6 {[%csl Rh4][%cal
Rg2g4]}) 25. Re1 Be8 26. e4 Bf8 27. Re2 Rb6 28. Bc7 Rc6 29. Bg3 Bg6 30. Rbe1
Kf7 31. Bf4 {[%cal Gg2g4]} Bh7 32. g4 Rb6 33. Nf1 Rc8 34. Bg3 Rb5 35. Rf2 Rc6
36. Ree2 Rcb6 37. Bc7 Rc6 38. Bg3 {[#] Both players have put their pieces on
good squares, although it is clear that Black is the one with the initiative.
After a lot of manoeuvring to bide time, the critical moment arrived on move
61.} Bg6 39. Bf4 Rc8 40. Ng3 Rd8 41. Kg2 Bh7 42. h4 Rd7 43. Nf1 Be7 44. Bg3 Rd8
45. Kg1 Rd7 46. Kg2 Rd8 47. Bc7 Rc8 48. Bg3 Bf8 49. Kg1 Rd8 50. Kg2 Rd7 51. Kg1
Rb3 52. Kg2 Rb6 53. Kg1 Rb5 54. Kg2 Rd8 55. Bc7 Rc8 56. Bg3 Be7 57. Kg1 Rc6 58.
Kg2 Bf8 59. Kg1 Rcb6 60. Bc7 Ra6 61. Bg3 {[#] How can Black strengthen his
position?} Rb3 $1 {[%cal Rf8a3] preparing to sacrifice a piece on a3 in order
to get a passed pawn.} (61... e5 $5 {is an interesting central breakthrough,
although it is not clear whether Black can actually win after} 62. dxe5 Bc5 63.
Ne3 dxe4 64. f4 Bxe3 65. Rxe3 f5 66. g5 Rd5 67. Rh2 Rb6 68. Ree2 $17) 62. Kg2
Bxa3 63. bxa3 Rxa3 64. Re3 $2 ({The only way to save the game was} 64. exd5
Rxc3 65. dxe6+ Rxe6 66. d5 $1 $132 Rxe2 67. Rxe2 Bd3 68. Re1 $13 {[%cal Bd5d8]}
a3 69. d6 a2 70. d7 Bxf1+ 71. Kxf1 Rxf3+ 72. Bf2 Rd3 73. Ra1 Rxd7 74. Rxa2)
64... Rb3 {The a-pawn is a runner now.} 65. exd5 (65. Nd2 a3 $1 66. Nxb3 cxb3
$19) 65... a3 $1 66. dxe6+ Rxe6 67. Rxe6 Kxe6 68. Re2+ Kd7 {[%cal Gh7b1]} 69.
Ra2 Rxc3 ({Black could win even more quickly with} 69... Rb2+ 70. Rxb2 axb2 71.
Nd2 b5 $1 {[%cal Bb5b4] with a decisive breakthrough.}) 70. Be1 {0-1 White
resigns.} 0-1

