1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Qb6 5. Qc1 $6 {Inaccurate opening play.} ({
The pawn should have been defended indirectly with} 5. Na3 {[%cal Ba3c4]} Qxb2
6. Nb5 {[%csl Bb2]}) 5... Nc6 6. c3 Nh5 $1 {Black has no reason not to win the
bishop pair here.} 7. Bg3 h6 8. Nbd2 d5 9. Bd3 Be7 10. O-O Nxg3 11. hxg3 O-O {
[%csl Bd4][%cal Be3e4] The structure may be similar to Kamsky-Carlsen from
Game 2, but there is one crucial difference - the position of the pawn on c5.
Because of the pressure against the d4-pawn, White cannot push e3-e4 as easily
as in that game.} (11... c4 $6 12. Bc2 {[%cal Be3e4] would indeed be like
Kamsky-Carlsen}) 12. a3 a5 13. a4 Bd7 14. Bb5 Rfd8 15. Re1 Rac8 16. Qd1 Nb8 17.
Bxd7 Nxd7 18. Qb3 Qxb3 19. Nxb3 b6 {The arising endgame is slightly more
pleasant for Black as he has a space advantage.} 20. Nc1 Rb8 {Preparing the
b5-break.} ({Pawn play is important in London endgames: it would have been a
good idea to grab more space on the kingside before starting active operations
on the other flank (principle of two weaknesses).} 20... h5 $5 21. Nd3 g5 {
[%csl Bg3,Bf2,Bg2]}) 21. Re2 Rdc8 22. Nd3 b5 ({It was more accurate to start
with} 22... c4 {to fix the b2-weakness.} 23. Nde5 Nf6 {[%cal Gb6b5]}) 23. axb5
Rxb5 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Bd4c5]} 24. Nfe5 $6 ({White should have traded off the
c-pawn.} 24. dxc5 $1 Nxc5 25. Nxc5 Bxc5 26. Ra2 Rcb8 27. Ne5 $10 {followed by
Nd3, when the b2-weakness would be adequately covered.}) 24... Nxe5 25. Nxe5
Bd6 26. Nd3 $2 (26. c4 {was the last chance to avoid the queenside bind.} dxc4
27. Nxc4 Be7 28. Rxa5 Rb4 29. b3 cxd4 30. exd4 Rxb3 $15) 26... c4 $17 27. Nc1
Rcb8 28. Ra2 a4 {The right plan, but...} ({Again, it was better to play} 28...
h5 {[%csl Bg3]} 29. Rc2 g5 {in order to eventually create the second weakness
on the kingside}) 29. Rc2 Rb3 30. g4 $1 {A useful move for the arising endgame.
} a3 31. bxa3 Rxa3 32. Rxa3 Bxa3 {Now, the c3-pawn is the base of the pawn
chain and the next target for Black.} 33. Ne2 Rb3 34. g3 $2 {[%cal Re2g3] It
was important to leave the g3-square for the knight.} ({Thus,} 34. f3 {was a
better way to centralize the king.} Kf8 35. Kf2 Ke7 36. e4 Bb2 37. Ke3 Kd6 38.
exd5 exd5 39. Kd2 Kc6 ({The point is that now} 39... g5 {would be met by} 40.
Ng3 {which is why White needs the g3-square!}) 40. Ng3 g6 41. Ne2 Kb5 42. Nf4
$132) 34... Kf8 35. Kg2 Ke7 36. Kf3 Kd6 37. e4 f6 38. exd5 exd5 39. Ke3 Bb2 40.
Kd2 g5 $1 {[%cal Re2g3] Correctly limiting the knight.} 41. Ng1 Ke6 $2 {
Too meek.} ({The winning plan was:} 41... Kc6 $1 42. Nf3 Kb5 43. Ne1 Ka4 44.
Ng2 Rb5 45. Ne3 Kb3 {and Black should win thanks to the superior position of
his forces and a big weakness on c3.} 46. Nd1 Ba3 47. Ne3 Ra5 48. Nd1 (48. Nf5
Bb2 49. Ne3 Ra2 50. Kd1 Ra1+ 51. Kd2 Ra5 $22 $19 52. Nf5 Ra2) 48... f5 49. gxf5
h5 50. Ne3 h4 51. gxh4 gxh4 52. Ke2 h3 53. Kf3 Ra8 $19) 42. f3 f5 43. Nh3 fxg4
44. fxg4 Ba3 45. Ke2 Bb2 46. Kd2 Ba3 47. Ke2 Bb2 48. Kd2 {1/2-1/2 The game is
a draw.} 1/2-1/2

