{[%evp 0,84,61,14,28,13,57,54,64,64,59,38,28,11,22,20,19,14,13,2,3,-2,25,13,22,
23,29,29,20,21,37,14,11,-17,41,30,24,23,38,44,40,39,50,34,41,22,24,22,43,37,12,
0,0,-34,-22,-27,-18,-12,-5,-57,-67,-67,-45,-45,-27,-10,-19,-34,-35,-45,-11,-33,
-27,-28,-36,-82,-79,-30,0,4,66,-83,-80,-258,-263,-278,-293]} 1. d4 (1. e4 c6 2.
d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 {This is the Caro-Kann move
order from which we reach the reversed Carlsbad pawn structure.} Bg4 7. Qb3 Qd7
({A fashionable continuation} 7... e5 $5 {is discussed in Game 8:
Demchenko-Postny}) 8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 Bd6 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. O-O O-O 12. Rfe1 Ne7
13. Ne5 Bf5 14. a4 {An important move to keep Black's typical queenside
minority attack in check.} Bxd3 15. Nxd3 {[%csl Gd3]} Rab8 16. a5 {[%csl Ga5]
[%cal Rb7b5] Aggressive play. Now, the b7-pawn is fixed. Carlsen's strategy in
this game, as we will see, was to play on queenside.} Ng6 17. g3 Rfc8 18. Qb4
Qxb4 19. Nxb4 {[#] Please suggest a plan for Black?} Ne7 $1 {Improving the
worst placed piece to an ideal square (d6), from where it controls many other
important squares.} 20. Nd3 Nf5 {[#] Please suggest a plan for White?} 21. Ra4
$5 {[%csl Bb7][%cal Be1a1,Ba1a3,Ba3b3,Ba4b4,Bd3c5] Carlsen planned to bring
both his rooks to the b-file and play Nc5 to attack the b7-pawn.} Nd6 22. Kf1
Rc7 23. Ke2 g6 24. Rb4 Kg7 25. Ra1 Nfe4 26. Nxe4 Nxe4 27. Ra3 Nd6 28. Nc5 Re8
29. Rab3 $6 {An ambitous approach.} (29. Nd3 $11 {was safer}) 29... Ree7 {
Defense on the seventh rank - instructive play.} ({Yet, a surprisingly strong
pawn sacrifice:} 29... e5 $1 30. Nxb7 Nc4 31. Kd3 (31. dxe5 Rxe5+ 32. Kd3 Re1
$40 {[%csl Yd3]}) 31... exd4 32. cxd4 Re1 $36 {would have given Black a
dangerous initiative against the exposed white king.}) 30. f4 (30. Nd3 {
is, once again, a safer move. Carlsen remains ambitious.}) 30... h6 31. Kf3 Kf6
{Firouzja, on the other hand, was not ambitious and a draw was soon agreed.} ({
However, Black could have played for more with} 31... f6 $15 {[%cal Gg6g5,
Ge6e5] preparing pawn breaks ...e5 and ...g5 as in Artemiev's game. For
example:} 32. h4 e5 $1 33. fxe5 fxe5 34. dxe5 Nc4 $36 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc4d2]
and White seems to be in trouble.}) 32. g4 Kg7 33. Kg3 Kf6 (33... g5 $15) 34.
h3 Kg7 35. Kg2 Kf6 36. Kg3 Kg7 37. Kg2 Kf6 38. Kg3 {1/2-1/2 (38) Carlsen,M 
(2863)-Firouzja,A (2728) Lichess.org INT 2020}) 1... d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 cxd4 4.
exd4 Nc6 5. c3 {We have the reversed Carlsbad pawn structure, which arises
quite often in the London system. In the following two games, we will see
typical endgames with knights and rooks (diagonal moving pieces are traded off)
.} Bf5 6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 e6 8. Nf3 Bd6 9. Bg3 Nf6 10. Nbd2 h5 $5 {[%cal
Be8c8]} 11. O-O-O Qc7 12. Kb1 O-O-O 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. Ng5 Rhf8 15. Qg3 {
White offers the queen trade, expecting to open the h-file. However, Artemiev
forces the endgame on his own terms:} Ng4 16. Rdf1 Ne7 $1 {preparing ...Nf5.}
17. Qxd6 Rxd6 {This endgame looks rather balanced, yet Black has a slightly
more flexible pawn structure (a possibility of minority attack on the
queenside + central ...e5-break). In the game, Artemieve demonstrated
near-perfect play:} 18. h3 Nh6 19. Re1 Kd7 {[%cal Bf7f6]} 20. Nb3 ({It was
wiser to prevent Black from pushing ...g5, so} 20. Ngf3 f6 21. h4 {seemed more
to the point. Even after} Ng4 22. Re2 Ng6 23. g3 e5 24. Rf1 e4 25. Ne1 {
[%cal Gf2f3,Ge1g2] Black has a solid pawn structure and can get rid of the
backward f-pawn with a timely f2-f3 break.}) 20... b6 21. Nc1 f6 22. Nf3 g5 $15
{Black's space advantage guarantees him a slight edge.} 23. Nd3 Ng6 24. g3 Rh8
25. Kc2 Rc6 26. Kd2 Rcc8 27. Re2 Nf5 28. Rhe1 Rce8 29. b3 g4 {[%csl Be4] After
some maneuvering, Black increases his space advantage, while also securing
e4-outpost for the knight and fixing the f2-weakness.} 30. Ng1 Nd6 31. Kc2 Re7
32. Kb2 Rc8 33. h4 Ne4 34. Rc2 e5 $6 {Premature.} ({Some preparation was
needed:} 34... a5 {[%cal Rd3b4,Ge6e5] and if} 35. c4 Kd6 {[%cal Ge6e5]} 36. Ne2
{then} e5 {gives Black the upper hand.}) 35. Ne2 ({White could have equalized
with} 35. Nb4 $1 exd4 36. Nxd5 dxc3+ 37. Nxc3 $11) 35... Kd6 36. Rd1 Rec7 37.
dxe5+ fxe5 38. Nb4 Rc5 39. c4 {[#] The critical moment. Black has built a
great position. How should he proceed?} d4 $4 {Logical, but a blunder.} (39...
Ne7 $17 {was the right move, instead. Black keeps a strong pressure against
the f2-pawn in the endgame.} 40. cxd5 Rxc2+ 41. Nxc2 Nxf2 $19) 40. Nd3 $2 {
White missed his chance.} (40. Nxd4 $1 exd4 41. Re2 $1 $18 {The second move is
not easy to spot. Black is even losing now.}) 40... R5c7 41. Ne1 Nxf2 42. Ra1
Rf8 {0-1 White resigns.} 0-1

