{[%evp 0,47,18,18,18,18,18,18,22,13,17,11,7,14,14,6,29,29,29,-7,-4,-6,27,-19,
-19,-20,-19,-21,-24,-16,-4,-6,4,-4,12,-9,7,5,2,-28,1,0,0,-52,39,36,29,30,131,
123]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 e6 3. e3 d5 4. Nf3 Bd6 5. Bg3 O-O {A clever move order,
avoiding Bb5+ in some lines.} ({For example} 5... c5 6. Bb5+ $5 {forces Black
to play} Nc6 7. c3 O-O 8. Nbd2 {leading into one of the tabiyas of the London
system where White usually keeps a strong control over the e5-square.}) 6. Nbd2
(6. c4 $5 {seems more principled since Black has not played ...c5 himself yet.}
) 6... c5 7. c3 Qc7 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gb8d7] Another subtle move in the
opening. Black prepares Nbd7 in order to take control of the key e5-square.} 8.
Bd3 Nbd7 (8... Nc6 $2 9. dxc5) 9. O-O Bxg3 10. hxg3 e5 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5
Qxe5 {This is one of the typical pawn structures that can arise in this or
other branches of the London system. It resembles a reversed Slav/Caro-Kann
and Black is doing well thanks to his space advantage. We will examine a
couple of typical endgames that can arise here.} 13. Qf3 {[%csl Bg3][%cal
Bf3f4] White's idea is to exchange the queens on the f4-square.} ({We see a
better version of this endgame for Black in the following game:} 13. Nf3 Qe7
14. Qa4 g6 15. Rad1 b6 16. Qf4 Bb7 17. Bc2 Rad8 18. Qh6 Ne4 19. Qh4 Qxh4 20.
Nxh4 Rfe8 $15 {Black has a space advantage and is better centralized. Still,
White's position is pretty solid.} 21. Nf3 Kg7 22. Nd2 Nd6 23. Nf3 h5 24. Rfe1
{[#] After some back-and-forth manoeuvring, it is time for Black to choose a
plan. What would you play?} Re7 (24... Nc4 $5 {attacking the weak spot in
white position and trying to provoke more weaknesses, seems like the best
choice.} 25. b3 (25. Rb1 Bc8 26. Red1 (26. Bd3 Be6 27. Bxc4 dxc4 28. Rbd1 Kf6)
26... Be6 {[%cal Ba7a5,Bb6b5,Ba5a4]} 27. Nd2 Bg4) 25... Nd6 {[%csl Rc3,Ba4]
[%cal Rb6b5,Ba7a4] Black would have new targets, the c3-pawn and potentially
opening the a-file.}) 25. Bb3 Ne4 26. Nd2 Nf6 27. Nf3 Bc6 28. Ng5 {0-1 (53)
Sadhwani, R (2545)-Sevian, S (2660) Lichess.org INT 2020 Here, the strongest
plan is:} b5 29. a3 a5 $36 {[%cal Gd8b8] preparing to open the b-file. White
has very little counterplay to offer.}) 13... Bg4 14. Qf4 {[%cal Bf2f3,Bg3g4]}
Qxf4 $6 {This exchange helps White increase control of the centre and even
take initiative on the kingside.} ({Instead, Black should have played} 14...
Rfe8 {so that he could trade queens on his own terms} 15. Qxe5 Rxe5 {we
examine this pawn structure in the game Sadhwani-Sevian above.}) 15. gxf4 b6
16. Rfe1 {This was a blitz game, so there were several inaccuracies on both
sides.} ({The simplest was} 16. f3 Bd7 17. g4 $14) 16... Rfe8 17. Rac1 Rad8 ({
Black should have prevented kingside expansion with} 17... h5) 18. f3 Bd7 19.
Kf2 (19. g4) 19... Bc6 20. g4 $14 {Finally, White gets the pawns moving. Black
has quite an uncomfortable situation on the kingside.} h6 21. Rg1 Nd7 22. g5 (
22. Rh1 $5 $36 {[%cal Gd2f1,Gf1g3]}) 22... hxg5 23. Rxg5 g6 $4 {A blunder} ({
although White would keep a dangerous initiative even after} 23... Kf8 24. Rh1
g6 25. f5) 24. Bxg6 $18 {1-0 Black resigns.} 1-0

