of a wrong plan. This square should be reserved for the bishop.} Kf8 22. Kf2 b5
{The right approach since White has not played c4 himself.} 23. c3 Rac8 24. g4
h6 25. g3 Rd5 26. Rxd5 Nxd5 27. f4 ({White had one last chance to play} 27. c4)
27... Nb6 $1 $15 {[%cal Rc3c4] A strong move, stopping c3-c4 for good and
setting sights on the b2-weakness (with Na4). Compared to Idani-Sargissian,
the white pawn majority has been completely immobilized.} 28. Rd1 Ke7 29. Bg2
a5 30. Be4 {[#] 0-1 (54) Vokhidov,S (2526)-Meier,G (2626) Moscow 2019 What is
the best move for Black?} a4 $1 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Ga4a3] preparing to undermine
the c3-pawn or fix the b2-weakness.} (30... b4 $2 31. cxb4 axb4 32. Rd4) 31.
Rc1 (31. a3 {[%csl Bb2]} f6 32. Nd3 Nc4 $17 {[%csl Rb2]}) 31... f6 32. Nd3 Nc4
33. Ke2 h5 $1 $17 {Black can start playing for the second weakness.}) 21...
Rac8 22. Rxd8 Rxd8 23. Rd1 Rc8 ({Perhaps it was simpler to just go} 23... Rxd1+
24. Bxd1 $11) 24. c4 Kf8 25. f4 {White increases his space advantage on both
flanks. Black should have done something about it.} Ke7 ({The right move is,
of course,} 25... b5 {prompting a pawn exchange on the queenside, opening the
c-file and possibly getting d5-outpost for his knight.}) 26. Bf3 Rc7 $6 {
Too passive.} ({This wast the last chance to play} 26... b5 $1 27. Bb7 Rb8 28.
Bxa6 bxc4 29. Nxc4 Ra8 30. Rd6 Nd5 $132) 27. b4 Nd7 28. c5 $14 {White has
achieved his dream position in this endgame. Still, Black could have defended
much better.} Nb8 $6 {It is difficult to understand such passive play.} ({
Basic positional logic dictates that we trade our weak pieces for opponent's
strong ones:} 28... Nxe5 29. fxe5 Bc6) 29. Nc4 Bc6 30. Kf2 Bxf3 31. gxf3 {
[%cal Gh2g3,Gg2f3]} Nc6 32. a3 h5 33. g4 hxg4 34. fxg4 Nb8 $2 (34... Rd7 {
was the last chance to salvage a draw.}) 35. Kf3 Nd7 36. Rd6 g5 37. fxg5 Nxc5
38. bxc5 Rxc5 39. Rd4 Rxg5 40. Nb6 $18 {1-0 (58) Idani,P (2573)-Sargissian,G 
(2666) Dubai 2017}) 1... Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 d5 5. Nbd2 Bd6 6. Bg3
O-O 7. c3 Qc7 8. dxc5 {White typically plays this move as preparation for
e3-e4.} Qxc5 9. Bd3 Nbd7 10. Qe2 Re8 11. e4 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 {
This pawn structure is typical for the French defence, but it is not that
uncommon in the London system, either.} Nf6 14. Qd4 Qxd4 15. Nxd4 Bxg3 16. hxg3
{[#] The endgame is roughly balanced (we actually have a very similar endgame
in the Tarrasch French, please compare to the games above), but pawn
majorities on the opposite flanks make this an endgame in which all 3 results
are possible, depending on the skill of handling it.} Bd7 17. O-O-O g6 18. f3
h5 {Stopping any further expansion on the kingside.} 19. Rhe1 Kg7 20. Re5 Rac8
{So far, so good, but here White started to go astray with some strange
manoeuvres.} 21. Nb3 $6 ({Instead, White should put his queenside majority in
motion with} 21. c4 $11 {[%cal Gb2b3,Bc1b2] Please check the game
Idani-Sargissian above for comparison.}) 21... Rc7 22. Nc5 Bc6 23. Ne4 $2 {
The knight was placed much better on d4 than here. To make it worse, with his
next move, Black forces the rook to an even more awkward position} Nd7 24. Ra5
b6 25. Ra3 {[%csl Ra3]} Ne5 $17 {Suddenly, Black takes the initiative.} 26. Bc2
$2 {This loses material by force.} (26. Be2 {on the other hand,} Bxe4 27. fxe4
{is a positional disaster for White}) 26... Nc4 27. Rb3 Ne3 28. Rd2 Nxc2 29.
Rxc2 Ba4 $19 {0-1 White resigns.} 0-1

