Bf4 c5 3. e3 cxd4 4. exd4 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bd3 Bg4 {with a transposition into
the main game}) 1... c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4
7. Qb3 e5 $5 {This is a fashionable move, leading to some complications. In
the main line, we reach the endgame by force:} (7... Qd7 {is a quieter and
more solid option for Black.}) 8. h3 $1 {The critical move according to
opening theory.} Na5 9. Qc2 exf4 10. hxg4 Nxg4 11. Qe2+ Qe7 12. Nh3 f3 $1 {
[%csl Rd5] The arising endgame is evaluated as equal by most engines, but to a
human eye it seems easier to play with White because of a better pawn
structure.} 13. gxf3 $5 {This was Demchenko's improvement. On the surface,
doubling the pawns is a bit controversial, but it proved to be the right
strategy.} ({In their first game, Demchenko played} 13. Qxe7+ Bxe7 14. g3 Nc4
15. Bxc4 dxc4 {but transformation of the pawn structure seemed to work in
Black's favor.} 16. Nd2 Rc8 17. Nxf3 Kd7 18. Ne5+ Nxe5 19. dxe5 Rc5 20. O-O-O+
Kc6 21. f4 Rd5 {1/2-1/2 (60) Demchenko,A (2670)-Postny,E (2576) Teplice 2018})
13... Qxe2+ 14. Kxe2 Nf6 15. Nd2 Bd6 16. f4 $1 {[%csl Bf4] The doubled f-pawn
is actually quite useful. It supports Nf3-e5 maneuver, while also allowing
White to attack on the g-file should Black castle kingside.} Nh5 (16... O-O {
is probably a better choice, but White seems to have an easier position after}
17. Nf3 h6 18. Ne5 $14) 17. Kf3 g6 18. f5 $1 {The f-pawn proves its value once
again.} O-O-O 19. Nf1 $1 {A strong maneuver. The d5-pawn is already a clear
target.} Nc6 20. Ne3 $16 Ne7 21. Ng5 Rdf8 {[#] What should White play?} 22.
Rxh5 $1 {This exchange sacrifice seals the deal!} gxh5 23. f6 Ng6 24. Nxd5 {
Black center fell apart and White did not have a difficult task of converting
his huge positional advantage.} h6 25. Ne4 $18 Rd8 26. Rh1 h4 27. Bc4 Bb8 28.
Ne3 Rdf8 29. Nf5 Kd7 30. b4 {The pawns have been set in motion. White pieces
control all squares in the center and Black has no chance.} b6 31. Bb5+ Kd8 32.
c4 h5 33. c5 h3 34. Ned6 Bxd6 35. cxd6 Kc8 36. Ne7+ Kb7 37. Rc1 {1-0 Black
resigns.} 1-0

