{[#] In London endgames, pawn breaks are typically of crucial importance. In
this position, Karjakin played} 53... b4 $1 ({In case of something static like
} 53... Re7 $2 {White shuts down the queenside with} 54. b4 $16 {and proceeds
to press his advantage freely on the other flank.}) 54. cxb4 Rb7 (54... Kc6 $5
{was another way to target the b4-pawn.}) 55. g4 ({In the event of} 55. Kc3 {
Black would probably have to go} Kc6 {anyway.}) 55... Rxb4 56. Kc3 Rdb7 $132 {
Black has obtained counterplay that is sufficient at least for a draw.} 57.
Rfxf7 Rxb3+ 58. Kc2 Rb2+ 59. Kc1 Rxf7 60. Rxf7 Rb4 {Karjakin managed to win
this drawish rook endgame under time pressure.} 0-1

