{[#] In the game, Caruana erred with} 41... Kh7 $2 {"Incredible! I can say
I've played well so far, but it isn't time to relax yet! Work remains and only
one move consolidates the advantage. I thought there was no difference between
this and 41...g5, since 42.g5 is met by 42...Nc1 43.Rb2 Nd3, when there is no
check on b8. This error stemmed from overestimating the ...Nc1-d3 idea." - F.
Caruana} ({The right move was} 41... g5 $1 {(remember, pawn moves are very
important in the London endgames!) Here is a part of Caruana's analysis:} 42.
Re5 (42. Bg3 Rc1) 42... Kh7 43. Bg3 Kg6 (43... Rc1 44. Rxg5 Rxc3 45. d5 Re3 (
45... exd5 $2 46. Be5 $1 d4 47. Rxg7+ Kh6 48. g5+ Kh5 49. Bf6 $40) 46. d6 Rd3
47. Rb5 f6 $17) 44. d5 Nd2 45. h4 (45. Bf2 Nf1+ 46. Kg1 Ne3+ $19) 45... gxh4
46. Bf4 Nf1+ 47. Kh3 exd5 48. Rxd5 Ne3 $1 $17) (41... Nc1 42. Rb2 Nd3 43. Rb8+
Kh7 44. Bg3 $11) 42. g5 $1 {"Now I realised what I had done. My advantage is
of course still there but it is much more difficult to win." - F. Caruana} Nc1
43. Rc2 Nd3 44. Bg3 $15 0-1

