{[%evp 0,53,19,31,43,16,27,26,25,21,88,50,47,25,32,14,26,36,19,14,97,20,22,-1,
3,0,35,12,21,34,39,13,39,31,43,-11,-2,39,61,68,118,203,251,231,276,269,355,257,
284,284,349,349,644,352,653,780] We can often see people saying that the
London System is a boring setup that has nothing to do with the classical
openings. Some of them go even further by stating that playing the London is
the lazy man's approach to the opening. Nevertheless, when you start examining
the arising positions, you will see many structures which are typical for
classical openings. For example, we have Stonewall structure, Slav structure,
Caro-Kann structure, French type of positions, etc. Therefore, in order to be
a good London player, one should have a classical chess education. In this
line of thoughts, we can understand why recently this opening is getting so
popular at the top level. London gives you the chance to play positionally
justified chess and nevertheless show creativity in relatively less explored
positions. In our computer-driven times, finding such systems is far from easy.
When covering the variety of the London structures, I was forced to prioritize
certain aspects among others. I have tried to show the most characteristic
London structures while at the same time following the historical development
of the ideas. I hope that you will enjoy my work! First of all, I start with 2
examples which show what White wants to achieve in London.} 1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6
3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 c5 5. Nbd2 Be7 6. c3 O-O 7. Bd3 b6 8. Ne5 Bb7 {This position
is a good illustration of the philosophy behind the London System. White has a
stable centre and a dark-squared bishop which is outside the pawn chain. Since
white pieces are pointing towards the black king, White's long-term plans are
based on a kingside attack. Such an attack is positionally justified since
White has good central control. When speaking about central control, you
should pay special attention to the e5-knight. This knight is one of the main
assets for White. As we are going to witness on a number of occasions, the
battle for e5-square is a major topic in the London System. It's quite
instructive to see how Short has managed to build up a killing attack.} 9. Qf3
{I think that this is the most precise move order. Besides transferring the
queen to the kingside, White takes the e4-square under control. Otherwise, he
should always reckon with the idea ...Ne4 followed by ...f7-f6.} Nfd7 $6 {
This move is already dubious since the knight is going far away from the
kingside.} ({More popular is} 9... Nbd7 {Even in this case, however, Black
does not manage to solve his problems. The game usually follows with} 10. Qh3
g6 ({The move} 10... Re8 {will be dealt with in the next example.}) 11. Bh6 Re8
12. Ndf3 {[%cal Ge5f7,Gg8f7,Gf3g5] The second knight joins the attack. The
threat is 13. Nxf7 followed by Ng5.} Bf8 13. Bxf8 Nxf8 14. Qh6 {[%cal Gh2h4]
White's attack is already decisive. White is planning to proceed with h2-h4-h5.
}) 10. Qh3 g6 11. Ndf3 Nxe5 {This move plays into White's hands. Objectively
speaking, however, it's already difficult to provide Black with good advice.}
12. dxe5 $1 {This is the right way to recapture in such structures. The
e5-pawn gives White a space advantage on the kingside, thus increasing the
attacking potential.} Ba6 13. Bc2 {Of course, when possible White should
refrain from exchanging the light-squared bishops.} Nc6 14. Qh6 {White already
has an overwhelming attack. He is ready to follow with h2-h4-h5.} f5 15. g4 {
This move is a thematic reaction to the advance ...f7-f5. In this position,
however, White could have played in a more precise way.} ({More to the point
would have been} 15. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5,Gf3g5] threatening h4-h5 or Ng5. The game
is over.}) 15... Rf7 $2 {This is losing on the spot.} ({More tenacious would
have been} 15... d4 {when at least some precision is required from White:} 16.
Rg1 dxc3 17. bxc3 Qd5 18. gxf5 exf5 19. Bb3 c4 20. Ba4 $1 {This important move
is forcing the win. I provide the following lines as a justification.} Nb4 ({
Taking the knight with} 20... Qxf3 {does not help either. For example:} 21.
Rxg6+ hxg6 22. Qxg6+ Kh8 23. Qh6+ Kg8 24. Bxc6 Qg4 25. Bd5+ Rf7 26. Qe6 Raf8
27. Qxe7 Qg1+ 28. Ke2 Qxa1 29. Qg5+ Kh7 30. Qh6+ Kg8 31. e6 {with mate to
follow.}) 21. Nd4 Nd3+ 22. Kd2 Nxf4 23. exf4 Qf7 24. h4 $18 {[%cal Gh4h5]}) 16.
gxf5 exf5 17. Rg1 Qd7 18. h4 $18 {White is already winning. Short managed to
convert his advantage without any problems.} Bf8 19. Qg5 Re8 20. h5 Rg7 21.
hxg6 Rxg6 22. Bxf5 Ree6 23. Qh5 Rxg1+ 24. Nxg1 Nd8 25. O-O-O Kh8 26. Nh3 Qb7
27. Bg5 1-0

