{[%evp 0,69,26,26,31,31,31,31,30,28,28,25,31,23,27,-4,10,5,5,5,20,-10,19,6,10,
7,12,12,46,17,79,69,49,60,56,69,95,101,102,105,117,109,119,120,120,120,120,122,
125,116,128,124,130,130,120,129,131,131,137,133,230,249,262,277,311,417,410,
505,605,657,1182,1307] We shall now see how White's attack works against a
more stubborn defence. The first 9 moves repeat the previous game.} 1. d4 d5 2.
Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nd2 Be7 5. Bd3 O-O 6. Ngf3 c5 7. c3 b6 8. Ne5 Bb7 9. Qf3
Nbd7 {This is a better defence in comparison to 9...Nfd7 which was chosen by
the opponent of Nigel Short. Practice shows, however, that the d7-knight is
quite ineffective in the fight for the e5-square. In the later examples, we
are going to see that the best configuration is Bd6&Nc6.} 10. Qh3 Re8 {[%cal
Gd7f8,Gf8g6] Black is freeing the f8-square for the knight. He can even
consider the manoeuvre...Nf8-g6 which is a typical defensive device in such
structures. On the other hand, White has an easy way to prevent this idea.} 11.
Ndf3 {[%cal Ge5f7] Besides threatening Nxf7 followed by Ng5, White is ready to
meet ...Nf8 with Ng5.} Nxe5 ({In London structures, you should always consider
} 11... Ne4 {In this concrete position, Black's idea does not work in view of}
12. Nxd7 Qxd7 13. Ne5 Qd8 14. f3 Nf6 15. g4 {[%cal Gg4g5]} g6 16. O-O {[%cal
Gf4g5,Gh3h4,Gf3f4,Gf4f5] White is ready to proceed with Bg5, Qh4 followed by
f3-f4-f5. White's attack is unstoppable.} ({Another idea is to win an exchange
by means of} 16. Bb5 {Nevertheless, the text move is more consistent since it
works even if Black's queen is not on d8.})) ({As pointed out,} 11... Nf8 $2 {
runs into} 12. Ng5 $18) 12. Nxe5 {Whenever Black's knight is on f6, taking on
e5 with a knight makes more sense.} ({In a case of} 12. dxe5 $6 Ne4 {the
position is not so clear.}) 12... c4 $2 {This is an instructive positional
mistake. Since there is no longer tension in the centre, White has a free hand
on the kingside.} ({On the other hand, it's not so clear how Black should play.
For example, a move like} 12... Bd6 {is well met by} 13. O-O-O {[%cal Gg2g4,
Gg4g5] when White is ready to follow with g2-g4.}) 13. Bc2 b5 14. Ng4 {A
typical move. White provokes the weakening ...g7-g6. White's attack plays
itself.} g6 ({After} 14... Ne4 15. f3 f5 16. fxe4 fxg4 17. Qxg4 $18 {White is
winning.}) 15. Nh6+ Kg7 16. Be5 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gg2g4,Gg4g5] Remember this
thematic way of exploiting the weakness of the dark squares. The game is
basically over.} Bd6 17. f4 Bxe5 18. fxe5 Nh5 19. Nxf7 $1 {The final touch.
The remaining part of the game does not need comments. White is winning.} Kxf7
20. g4 Qg5 21. gxh5 Qxh5 22. Qxh5 gxh5 23. Bxh7 Rh8 24. Rf1+ Ke7 25. Bg6 Raf8
26. Ke2 Bc6 27. Rxf8 Rxf8 28. Rf1 Rxf1 29. Kxf1 h4 30. Kg2 a5 31. Kh3 Be8 32.
Bxe8 Kxe8 33. Kxh4 b4 34. Kg5 a4 35. a3 1-0

