{In the next 3 examples, we are going to see how Black should deal with
White's attacking constructions. In this game, Adams went for one of the most
critical setups against the London System.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 d5 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3
c5 {In my opinion, this is not the optimal move order for Black. The reason is
that White gets some extra options.} ({A more restrictive move order would be} 
4... Bd6 5. Bg3 O-O 6. Nbd2 c5 {and so on.}) 5. c3 Nc6 6. Nbd2 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O
8. Bd3 ({Since Black has committed to ...c7-c5 and ...Nc6 a bit early, White
can also play} 8. Bb5 {which was tried by Magnus Carlsen.}) 8... b6 9. Ne5 Bb7
10. f4 {We have reached a Stonewall type of position with colours reversed. In
comparison to the classical Stonewall positions, White has managed to activate
his problematic dark-squared bishop. This bishop can eventually join the
attack with Bh4. White is planning to start gradually transferring his pieces
to the kingside. Black, however, has an elegant way of neutralizing White's
pressure.} Ne7 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gf7f6] You can now see the point behind
developing the dark-squared bishop to d6 - the e7-square is available for the
knight. With his last move, Black actually starts fighting for the e4-square.
The immediate threat is ...Ne4 followed by ...f7-f6. Therefore, you should
play ...Ne7 only when after White had played f2-f4.} 11. Qf3 {The most logical
move. Besides activating his queen, White also covers the e4-square. Black,
however, has a nice manoeuvre at his disposal.} Nf5 12. Bf2 Be7 $1 {[%cal
Gf5d6,Gf6e4,Gf7f6] Remember this thematic idea. Black is planning ...Nd6
followed by ...Nfe4 and ...f7-f6. In my opinion, White is the one who should
care about equality.} 13. g4 Nd6 14. g5 Nfe4 {Mission completed! After
neutralizing White's ideas, Black can go for his queenside play. The most
typical way to start playing on the queenside is ...c5-c4 followed by ...
b6-b5-b4. The move .. .cxd4 is possible in two cases: 1) when White is forced
to recapture with the c-pawn, thus giving Black the possibility to play on the
c-file 2) when White castles long.} 15. O-O-O c4 $6 {This thematic move is not
the optimal way of handling this exact position.} ({Since White has already
castled long, playing} 15... cxd4 $1 {is making sense. The play might continue}
16. exd4 b5 17. h4 b4 18. cxb4 a5 {when Black's attack on the queenside is
faster. For example:} 19. b5 a4 20. a3 Qa5 21. Be1 Qb6 22. Qe2 Rac8+ 23. Kb1
Nxb5 24. Bxb5 Ba6 25. Nd7 Bxb5 $17 {with an obvious advantage for Black. 0-1 
(39) Sodomski, A (2006) -Fedorov,S (2399) ICCF email 2011}) ({Keeping
flexibility with} 15... b5 $2 {is a bad idea. White can force a draw in a
beautiful way:} 16. dxc5 $1 Nxc5 17. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 18. e4 $3 Ncxe4 19. Nxe4
Nxe4 20. g6+ $1 Kg8 21. Qh3 fxg6 22. Qxe6+ Kh7 23. Qxg6+ $11) 16. Bc2 $2 {
Karjakin misses his chance to complicate matters. After this move, his
position is simply lost.} ({Necessary was} 16. Bxe4 $1 dxe4 17. Qg4 b5 18. h4
b4 19. h5 a5 20. Nb1 Nf5 21. g6 fxg6 22. h6 $1 Qe8 23. hxg7 Kxg7 24. Rh2 $44 {
White has a decent compensation for the pawn.}) 16... b5 17. Qh3 b4 18. Nxe4
dxe4 $1 {Another instructive moment. When possible, we always try to recapture
on e4 with a pawn. In this way, the d5-square is available for the bishop.} 19.
Be1 Bd5 20. Rg1 b3 21. axb3 cxb3 22. Bb1 f5 $1 {Another nice idea. Adams wants
to eliminate White's space advantage on the kingside, thus ruling out all
ideas based on Ne5-g4-f6.} 23. gxf6 Bxf6 24. Rg4 Nf5 {[%cal Gd8a5,Ga5a1,Ga7a3]
The game is over. Black is planning to follow with ...Qa5-a1 followed by ...
a7-a5-a4-a3.} 25. Kd2 Qa5 $19 26. Ke2 Bxe5 27. dxe5 Rad8 28. Kf2 Qa1 29. Bd2
Bc4 30. Qh5 Qxb2 31. Ke1 Rxd2 0-1

