{This game is quite similar to the previous example. Instead of castling long,
Antoaneta Stefanova opted for} 15. Qh3 {White believes that the king will be
safer in the centre than on queenside. As this game proves, however, this is
not true.} Rc8 {[%cal Gc5c4] Black is preparing the advance ...c5-c4.} 16. Rd1
c4 17. Bc2 b5 {[%cal Gb5b4] Black is strategically better. His queenside pawns
are rolling while White does not have any play on the kingside.} 18. Rg1 $2 {
White insists on keeping the king in the centre.} ({More logical would have
been} 18. a3 a5 19. O-O {when it's still not easy for Black to develop his
queenside play.}) 18... b4 $1 {Of course! Navara does not need to spend time
on the preparatory ...a7-a5. Black is already winning.} 19. Nxe4 dxe4 20. Ng4 {
White's only hope is based on Nf6 at some point. Therefore, Black should be
careful.} bxc3 21. bxc3 Qa5 22. Kd2 Bd5 $2 {This terrible mistake not only
spoils the advantage but also makes White's position preferable.} ({The
cautious} 22... Nf5 $1 23. Nf6+ Bxf6 24. gxf6 g6 $19 {Would have given Black a
decisive advantage. White's mating attempts simply don't work. For example:}
25. Rg5 {[%cal Gg5f5,Gh3h6]} Qd8 26. Rxf5 exf5 27. Bh4 Qa5 28. Bg5 h5 $19 {
Black is winning.}) 23. a4 $2 ({White should have played} 23. Nf6+ $1 {when
after} Bxf6 24. gxf6 g6 25. Rg5 $1 {is an important attacking resource. Now,
Black should be very careful in order not to lose immediately.} Ne8 (25... Qd8
26. Rh5 Qxf6 27. Rxh7 Nf5 28. Rg1 Rb8 29. Rg4 $16 {[%cal Gf2h4,Gg4g5]}) 26. f5
$1 $36) 23... Rb8 {The game is now over.} 24. Rb1 Rb3 $1 {An elegant exchange
sacrifice in the style of Petrosian. The remaining part of the game does not
need comments.} 25. Bxb3 cxb3 26. Nf6+ Bxf6 27. gxf6 g6 28. Rg5 Qxa4 29. Ke1
Qa2 30. Rd1 Bc4 0-1

