{The next example shows when Black should release the central tension with the
move ...cxd4. After the moves} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 d5 4. e3 c5 5. c3 Nc6
6. Nbd2 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3 b6 9. Ne5 Bb7 10. f4 Ne7 {we reach the position
from the games Karjakin - Adams and Stefanova - Navara. In this game, Sandipan
decided to stop ...Ne4 with} 11. Qb1 {Besides taking control of the e4-square,
White puts pressure on the diagonal b1-h7 as well. On the downside, with his
last move, White restricts the mobility of his queen's rook. Additionally, the
queen is far away from the kingside.} Ng6 {This is a decent approach.} ({
The classical way of dealing with Qb1 is} 11... g6 {[%cal Ge7f5] insisting on .
..Nf5.}) 12. Nxg6 $6 {This exchange is dubious. Without the e5-knight, Black
does not have worries. He can already start playing on the queenside.} ({
More natural would be} 12. O-O {when Black's best is the thematic} a5 $1 {
[%cal Ga5a4,Gb7a6] There are two ideas behind this move: 1) exchanging the
light-squared bishops via a6 2) destroying White's queenside structure by
means of ...a5-a4-a3. The game might continue} 13. a4 Qc7 14. Re1 Ba6 $11 {
Black doesn't have problems whatsoever. After exchanging the light-squared
bishops, he can start preparing the advance ...b6-b5.}) 12... hxg6 13. Bh4 cxd4
$1 {This is the most instructive moment in the game. Black takes on d4 when
White is forced to recapture with the c-pawn. In this way, Black can start
playing along the c-file.} 14. cxd4 Bb4 $6 {Maybe this move is a waste of time.
} ({Instead, Black could have started with} 14... Qd7 {[%cal Gb7c6,Gc6b5]
planning to exchange the light-squared bishops by employing the manoeuvre...
Bc6-b5.}) 15. Qd1 Qd7 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. O-O Bc6 $1 {Better latter than never.
Black managed to find the right plan. The next few moves are quite logical.}
18. Nf3 Bb5 19. Rc1 Bxd3 20. Qxd3 Rfc8 21. Qa6 $2 {This mistake allows Black
to obtain a huge advantage.} ({More logical would have been} 21. Qb1 {planning
to exchange all the rooks. In this case, White's position is holdable.}) 21...
Rc7 $6 {Black misses his chance.} ({After} 21... b5 $1 {[%cal Ga8b8] Black
obtains a huge advantage due to White's misplaced queen.}) 22. Rxc7 Qxc7 23.
Qa4 $6 {Once again, not the most precise move. Black can now take full
advantage of the c-file.} ({More tenacious would have been} 23. Qe2 Rc8 24. a3
Bd6 25. Ne1 {[%cal Ge1d3] when Black still needs to prove his advantage.})
23... Qc4 24. g3 Rc8 25. a3 $2 {Mistake in a difficult position.} Bd2 $19 {
Black is winning a pawn and the game is over.} 26. Qxc4 Bxe3+ 27. Kg2 Rxc4 28.
Rd1 Rc2+ 29. Kh3 Rf2 30. Nh4 g5 0-1

