{The setup that we have been examining in the previous 3 examples has been
gradually established as a reliable antidote to White's strategy. Therefore,
White started looking for alternative ways to handle the position. White
players started to test different attempts based on saving a tempo on Bg3. In
this case, however, White should accept doubled pawns on the f-file. This
structure is fundamental for your understanding of the London System. The next
few model games are designed to help you better understand this structure for
both colours. As an introduction, we will take a brief look at the blitz game
Carlsen - Anand, 2017. After} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Bd6 {Carlsen
played} 5. Nbd2 {White saves a tempo on Bg3 and keeps developing his pieces.
The important pawn structure arises after} Bxf4 6. exf4 {At this point, we
shall consider the most important aspects of this pawn structure. With a pawn
on f4, White has better control of the important e5-square. Additionally, he
can make use of the semi-open e-file. In some cases, Black should reckon with
the advance f4-f5. On the flip side, White's central structure is less
flexible now. Contrary to the positions with a pawn on e3, now Black will not
worry about the eventual e3-e4. At the same time, with a pawn on f4, the
d4-pawn is a bit more vulnerable. This game shows how White can create a
central tension by using his c-pawn.} Qd6 7. g3 b6 {[%cal Gc8a6] Before
playing the thematic .. .c7-c5, Black is planning to exchange the
light-squared bishops via a6.} 8. c3 O-O 9. Bd3 Ba6 10. Bxa6 {Even though
White lost a temp with his bishop, Black should waste some time to improve his
misplaced a6-knight.} Nxa6 11. Qe2 Nb8 12. Ne5 c5 {This is an important
position. You shall remember that when White has a knight on d2 and cannot
recapture on d4 with a piece Black wants to play ...cxd4. If White recaptures
with the c-pawn, his d2-knight will be misplaced. In such a case, Black can
start playing along the c-file. Therefore, Carlsen played} 13. Ndf3 {Now,
White is ready to recapture on d4 with a knight.} Ne4 {Black is planning to
follow with ...f7-f6. Even though this move drives the knight away, it
slightly weakens the king. This vulnerability might become significant if
White manages to create tension in the centre. A typical way to achieve such
tension is the well-timed c3-c4 or dxc5 followed by c3-c4.} ({After} 13... Nc6
{White can play} 14. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5,Gh5h6] As we will discuss later, the
advance of the h-pawn is a new trend in the London System. Actually, we can
say that pushing the h-pawn is currently fashionable in many openings. This
trend is inspired by AI-based engines such as Alpha Zero and Leela. In earlier
days, people were mainly playing h2-h4-h5 with the idea to deliver a mate
after opening the h-file. The new approach is to push the pawn all the way to
h6 and keep it as an important asset until the endgame. In all kind of
endgames, such a pawn will be a tremendous force. At the same time, even in
the middlegame, the h6-pawn will restrict the activity of Black's pieces. The
opponent always needs to reckon with some tactical ideas on the kingside.
Whenever Black blocks the pawn by means of ...h7-h6, White has the idea of
attacking by means of g4-g5. White's next moves would be Kf1-g2 followed by
h4-h5-h6. Black does not have a favourable way of releasing the central
tension. For example,} cxd4 {is well met by} 15. Nxc6 Qxc6 16. Nxd4 $14 {
[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge1f1,Gf1g2,Gh4h5,Gh5h6,Ga1e1] When White has an easier game.})
14. O-O f6 15. Ng4 {A slight inaccuracy which is typical for blitz games.} ({
More precise would have been} 15. Nc4 $1 Qe7 16. Rad1 Nc6 17. Ne3 {[%cal Gc3c4,
Gf4f5] When White is planning to proceed with c3-c4 or even f4-f5 in some
cases. At this point, we can see the drawbacks behind ...f7-f6.}) 15... Nc6 16.
dxc5 {Taking on c5 followed by c3-c4 is a thematic way to release the tension
in the centre. On the other hand, I think that when possible White should opt
for c3-c4 without including dxc5.} ({In the concrete position, going for c3-c4
without taking on c5 was possible. For example, after} 16. Rad1 Rad8 17. c4
Rfe8 18. Ne3 {White keeps some pressure.}) 16... bxc5 17. Rad1 f5 $6 {Giving
the e5-square is not desirable.} ({Anand should have preferred the flexible} 
17... Rad8 18. c4 Qc7 19. Ne3 {In this structure, White's idea is to transfer
his e3-knight to d3 after provoking the advance ...d5-d4.} d4 20. Nc2 f5 21.
Nce1 Rfe8 22. Nd3 {Even though the position is objectively equal, it's
slightly easier to play with White. After driving the e4-knight away, White
will have annoying pressure on the e-file. At the same time, Black's passed
pawn is safely blocked.}) 18. Nge5 Rab8 19. c4 Nxe5 20. Nxe5 {Now, White
managed to weaken the e5-square without wasting time as in the line with 17...
Rad8. The lack of constructive plans makes Black's play very difficult from a
practical point of view.} Rfd8 21. Rfe1 Qa6 22. f3 Nf6 23. b3 {Magnus prefers
to keep the tension.} ({Entering a position with hanging pawns was an
interesting option as well. For example, after} 23. cxd5 Qxe2 24. Rxe2 exd5 25.
Rc1 Rdc8 26. Rec2 Kf8 27. b3 $14 {White keeps an annoying pressure.}) 23...
Rbc8 24. Rc1 {[%cal Gc1c2,Ge1c1] By putting an indirect pressure on c5, White
is trying to provoke the advance ...d5-d4.} d4 25. Nd3 Rd6 $6 {The rook is
misplaced on d6.} ({More to the point would have been} 25... Re8 {keeping the
d6-square available for the queen.}) 26. Rc2 Nd7 27. Qg2 {[%cal Gc2e2]} Qb6 28.
Rce2 {It is hard to criticize a human move played in a blitz game. The game
move, however, is a bit slow. I will leave the remaining part of the game
without comments since the time-trouble has a huge impact on the quality of
the game. Eventually, Magnus managed to win.} ({The most precise would have
been to immediately start the kingside attack with} 28. g4 a5 29. h4 a4 30.
bxa4 Qa6 31. h5 {[%cal Gh5h6] with h5-h6 to follow. White's attack is very
dangerous.}) 28... a5 29. Rb2 Rb8 30. Qd2 Qc7 31. Qd1 h6 32. Rbe2 Qb6 33. h4 a4
34. Rb2 axb3 35. axb3 Qa7 36. Kh2 Ra6 37. Qe2 Rab6 38. g4 fxg4 39. fxg4 Qc7 40.
g5 hxg5 41. hxg5 e5 42. fxe5 Re6 43. Qe4 Rbe8 44. Qd5 Nb6 45. Qxc5 Qd8 46. Rg2
Rf8 47. Qb5 Rf3 48. Nc5 Rg6 49. e6 Qd6+ 50. Kg1 Rxg5 51. Ne4 1-0

