{[%evp 0,59,22,22,18,17,22,17,17,17,23,6,2,2,21,21,21,16,18,16,19,16,21,16,23,
23,25,26,26,33,31,34,38,48,35,41,60,59,50,42,64,47,82,61,56,51,59,27,49,50,107,
51,76,112,177,180,137,154,344,362,821,948] Now, we shall take a look at how
the legendary grandmaster Eugenio Torre executed a rather similar idea. After} 
1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nd2 Bd6 5. Ngf3 Bxf4 6. exf4 c5 $6 {This
advance is premature. Usually, Black starts with ...b7-b6 and plays this move
after the exchange of the light-squared bishops. The experience GM immediately
forced the transition into a favourable pawn structure with} 7. dxc5 $1 Qc7 8.
g3 Qxc5 9. Bd3 {We have the same type of position as in the previous game.} O-O
10. O-O b6 {[%cal Gc8a6]} 11. Qe2 {It's important to prevent Black from
exchanging the bishops via a6. Now, White can start his fight for the dark
squares in the centre.} Nc6 12. c3 Bb7 13. Rfe1 Rfe8 14. Nb3 {[%cal Gb3d4] In
this game, White brings his knight to d4 via an alternative route.} ({The move
} 14. Ne5 {was still possible. Nevertheless, with a bishop on b7, White should
always watch for ...d5-d4 ideas. That's why I would prefer 14.Nb3.}) 14... Qd6
15. Rad1 Rad8 16. Nbd4 Nxd4 17. Nxd4 {White managed to obtain complete central
control. This is a dream position for White in the structure with doubled
pawns on the f-file. Black does not have any ideas at his disposal.} Qb8 18.
Qe5 $5 {White wants to force the transition in a thematic French endgame which
is horrible for Black.} ({Another option would have been the Alpha Zero like} 
18. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5,Gh5h6] trying to create weaknesses on the kingside.}) 18...
Nd7 ({After} 18... Qxe5 19. fxe5 Nd7 20. Bb5 a6 21. Bxd7 Rxd7 22. f4 {[%csl
Rb7,Gd4][%cal Gg3g4,Gg1f2,Gf2g3,Gf4f5] White has a classical advantage -
strong knight against bad bishop. The plan here is fairly simple - gain space
on the kingside by means of g4-g5 followed by f4-f5. Of course, this should be
done after careful preparation. Black is doomed to passivity.}) 19. Qh5 {
Since Black wants to exchange the queens on his own terms, Torre uses the
opportunity to bring the queen into the attack.} g6 20. Qh4 Kg7 21. Bb5 $1 {
Once again, we see this thematic move. By exchanging Black's only good piece,
White achieves his dream position - good knight against a bad bishop.} a6 22.
Bxd7 Rxd7 23. Re5 Qd8 24. Qg4 Rde7 25. Rde1 Kh8 26. h4 $18 {The h-pawn joins
the attack. Black can do nothing. White is winning.} Rc7 27. h5 Bc8 28. hxg6 f6
29. Rh5 e5 30. Qh4 1-0

