{After understanding what White wants to achieve in this structure, it's time
to take a look at Black's antidotes. In this game, GM Kuljasevic shows how
Black should build his strategy. The first 10 moves repeat the game Carlsen -
Anand.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Bd6 5. Nbd2 Bxf4 6. exf4 Qd6 7. g3
b6 {[%cal Gc8a6]} 8. c3 O-O 9. Bd3 Ba6 10. Bxa6 Nxa6 11. a4 {Instead of
Carlsen's 11.Qe2, the Slovenian GM starts gaining space on the queenside. I
don't like this approach since White's queenside structure loses its
flexibility. After a2-a4, it will be very difficult for White to create
tension in the centre by employing his ideas based on c3-c4. In such a case,
the b4-square will be weak.} c5 12. Qe2 Nb8 13. O-O Nc6 {[%cal Gc5d4] Black
creates his usual positional threat - ...cxd4. Therefore, White played} 14. Qe3
{when after} Rac8 15. Rfd1 Rfd8 16. Kg2 {GM Kuljasevic demonstrated an
instructive manoeuvre -} Ng4 17. Qd3 Nh6 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gh6f5,Gc5d4,Rc3d4]
The idea ...Ng4-h6-f5 shows a deep understanding of the pawn structure. Black
is planning to put additional pressure on d4 by playing ...Nf5. As we know,
the idea is to force White to recapture with a pawn on d4.} 18. Ne5 cxd4 $1 {
This move marks the beginning of a well-evaluated sequence. After} 19. Nxc6
Qxc6 20. Qxd4 Nf5 {It turns out that White cannot hold the d4-square. Black
will play ...d5-d4 on the next move.} 21. Qd3 d4+ 22. Qf3 Qe8 {Black wants to
get a more complex position.} ({In my opinion, simpler would have been} 22...
Qxf3+ 23. Nxf3 dxc3 24. Rxd8+ Rxd8 25. bxc3 Kf8 $15 {with a stable advantage.})
23. Ne4 $6 {This move allows the activation of the knight.} ({Better would
have been} 23. a5 dxc3 24. bxc3 {when White's dynamic potential compensates
Black's better structure. Additionally, it's clear that every pawn exchange
brings the draw closer.}) 23... dxc3 24. Nxc3 Nd4 25. Qb7 Rd7 26. Qe4 f5 27.
Qd3 {Preparing ...Qa8 but allowing simplifications.} Rcc7 $6 {[%cal Ge8a8]} ({
More precise was} 27... Rdd8 {[%cal Ge8c6] with the idea of ...Qc6. Now, 28.
Nb5 runs into 28...Nc2-+.}) 28. Nb5 Nxb5 29. Qxb5 Qa8+ 30. Kg1 Qd8 1/2-1/2

