{The last game featuring the structure with doubled f-pawns is the best
illustration of Black's plan.} 1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 Bd6 5. Nbd2
Bxf4 6. exf4 b6 {I think that this is the most logical approach. It's not
clear whether the inclusion of the moves 6...Qd6 7.g3 is in Black's favour.} 7.
c3 O-O 8. g3 $6 {I think that this move is dubious. With his last move, White
only wastes time.} ({White's most dangerous plan is} 8. h4 {with the thematic
idea of pushing the pawn all the way to h6.} c5 9. h5 h6 10. Ne5 {[%cal Gg2g4,
Gg4g5] After provoking ...h7-h6, White goes for the thematic g2-g4-g5.} cxd4 ({
A high-profile game saw} 10... Bb7 11. Ndf3 Nc6 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13. Bd3 Rc8 14.
Qe2 Rc7 15. a3 $14 {with a slight advantage for White. White can gradually
build his kingside attack while Black's counterplay is far from obvious. 1/2-1/
2 (30) Giri,A (2768)-Vitiugov,N (2747) Wijk aan Zee 2020}) 11. cxd4 Ba6 12. g4
Bxf1 13. Kxf1 {The position is around equal but Black should be careful. For
example, after} Nfd7 14. g5 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Nc6 16. Qg4 $36 {White has some
kingside initiative.}) 8... c5 9. Bd3 Ba6 10. Bxa6 Nxa6 11. Qe2 Nc7 $1 {
So far we have been mainly examining the manoeuvre...Nb8-c6. Stefanova,
however, is planning to bring her knight to d6 via e8. The d6-square is a
perfect spot for the knight.} 12. O-O Nce8 13. Ne5 Nd6 14. Nb3 $2 {This move
is too passive. White plays into Black's hands.} ({Better would have been to
opt for a dynamic approach with} 14. c4 {Even in this case, however, Black is
doing fine after} Nf5 15. dxc5 bxc5 $132 {with a decent counterplay.}) 14...
Qc7 15. Rae1 a5 {[%cal Ga5a4,Ga4a3] Pushing the a-pawn is a typical idea in
such structures. The idea is ...a5-a4-a3, thus ruining White's queenside
structure.} 16. a3 a4 17. Nd2 cxd4 $1 {With a white knight on d2, taking on d4
is favourable for Black.} 18. cxd4 Rfc8 {This is the dream position for Black.
She will combine the play along the c-file with the pressure on the weak pawns
on d4 and b2. White does not have counterplay.} 19. Nd3 Nfe4 $6 {This natural
move is actually dubious.} ({After} 19... Nf5 20. Nf3 Qc4 $17 {Black is
winning the d4-pawn.}) 20. Rc1 Qb7 21. Nb4 {This pointless move gives Black
time to organize his play.} ({After} 21. Nxe4 Nxe4 22. Rc2 {[%cal Gf1c1] White
has a normal position.}) 21... Nxd2 22. Qxd2 Rc4 23. Rxc4 Nxc4 24. Qe2 Rc8 25.
Re1 Nd6 {[%cal Gc8c4] Besides stopping the advance f4-f5, Black prepares ...
Rc4 as well. The vulnerability of the d4-pawn starts telling. Another passive
move that makes White's position strategically hopeless.} 26. Qd3 $2 ({White
should have opted for} 26. g4 {gaining space on the kingside and keeping the
option of playing f4-f5 at some point.}) 26... g6 27. Kg2 b5 28. h4 h5 29. Re2
Rc4 {[%cal Gd6f5,Gb7b6]} 30. Rxe6 $2 {A desperation in a difficult position.
Black is already winning.} ({White should have accepted the passive position
after} 30. Nc2 $17) 30... fxe6 31. Qxg6+ Kf8 32. Qxe6 Nf7 33. Qf6 Qe7 34. Qb6
Qe4+ 35. Kh2 Rc1 36. Qb8+ Kg7 0-1

