{Now we shall see two high-profile games featuring the advance of the h-pawn.
As we have seen in some of the previous examples, gaining space on the
kingside by means of h2-h4-h5-h6 has recently become quite fashionable in the
London System. Since the game Firouzja - Duda has been discussed in the
lecture of GM Eljanov, I will only briefly cover some important aspects
related to the advance of the h-pawn.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 Bd6
5. Nbd2 O-O 6. Ne5 {Recently, the lines based on the early Ne5 became very
popular. In the top-level practice, playing early Ne5 without committing to
Bg3 indicates White's intention to go for h2-h4. The current game is not an
exception.} c5 7. c3 Qc7 8. Bd3 b6 9. h4 $1 {White does not try to prevent ...
Ba6. The entire procedure of exchanging the light-squared bishops and
rerouting the a6-knight takes a lot of time. Meanwhile, White will gain space
on the kingside.} Ba6 10. Bxa6 Nxa6 11. h5 Nd7 {This has been Black's main
continuation so far. Nevertheless, the arising positions are slightly
favourable for White.} ({As indicated by Pavel Eljanov, a decent try would be} 
11... h6 $5 {[%cal Gc5d4,Ge3d4,Ga6c5] stopping h5-h6 and planning to proceed
with ...cxd4 followed by ...Nc5. On the other hand, the h6-pawn can be used as
a hook for White's g2-g4-g5. Even though the arising positions are quite
complicated and double-edged, it seems that Black can maintain the balance.})
12. Ndf3 {White keeps fighting for the control of the e5-square.} ({Another
thematic attempt is} 12. h6 g6 13. Nxd7 Qxd7 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Qe2 Nb8 {
This position was reached in the game ½-½ (34) Demchenko, A (2655)-So, W 
(2767) Khanty-Mansiysk 2019. At this point, the simple} 16. O-O {would have
given White a slight advantage. The h6-pawn reduces the activity of the
opponent's pieces since Black should always reckon with some tactical ideas
based on this pawn. Therefore, White should look for opportunities to open the
centre with e3-e4. Depending on the concrete circumstances, he can either play
e3-e4 immediately or after dxc5. Below, I provide some short sample lines.} Nc6
{From this position, the knight puts pressure on the centre but is far away
from the kingside.} ({The alternative} 16... Nd7 {is well met by} 17. e4 $1 {
The following lines are a good illustration of the importance of the h6-pawn.}
Qf4 ({Opening the c-file with} 17... cxd4 18. cxd4 {is even more dangerous for
Black. Now, in many cases, he should reckon with ideas based on Rac1-c7.} Qf4 (
{In a case of} 18... dxe4 19. Nxe4 {White's initiative is overwhelming.} Qf4 ({
After} 19... Qe7 20. Rac1 {[%cal Gc1c7] Black has no favourable way of dealing
with Rc7. The following line is very instructive:} Rac8 $2 ({Black should play
} 20... Nf6 21. Nxf6+ Qxf6 22. Qe5 {which transposes to the line given below.})
21. Qb5 $1 {[%cal Gb5d7,Ge4f6] It turns out that Black has no good way of
preventing the threat of Qxd7.} Rxc1 ({The alternative} 21... Nf6 {runs into}
22. Qe5 {[%csl Gh6]} Nh5 23. d5 $18 {Once again, we can see the importance of
the h6-pawn.}) 22. Rxc1 f5 23. Rc7 $18 {White is winning.}) 20. Rac1 {This is
the most ambitious approach.} ({The idea} 20. Qe3 {is also possible. In this
case we have a position which is similar to the lines with 18...Qf4.}) 20...
Nf6 ({Black has no time to capture the h6-pawn. For example, after} 20... Qxh6
$4 21. Rc7 Rad8 22. Rxd7 $18 {White is winning.}) 21. Nxf6+ Qxf6 22. Qe5 Qxe5
23. dxe5 $18 {[%csl Rg8,Gh6] This endgame is lost for Black. Inevitably White
will get one of his rooks on the seventh rank. At the same time, due to the
h6-pawn, the black king can never get out of the cage. This position shows the
power of the h6-pawn in endgame positions.}) 19. Qe3 $16) 18. Qe3 Qxe3 19. fxe3
dxe4 20. Nxe4 f5 21. Ng5 {[%csl Gg5,Gh6] Once again, Black has a lot of
problems. The construction Ng5+h6 paralyzes Black's pieces.}) 17. dxc5 bxc5 18.
Rad1 {[%cal Ge3e4] White is ready to proceed with e3-e4. As we have seen in
the previous lines when the position opens up, Black starts experiencing
problems due to the h6-pawn.}) 12... f6 13. Nd3 cxd4 $2 {This is already an
important mistake. Now, White will win an exchange.} ({An instructive position
arises after} 13... c4 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Nf4 Nc7 16. Nh4 ({Another possibility
is} 16. h6 g6 17. O-O {As we know, with a pawn on h6, White will try to open
the position. A possible idea would be Qe2 followed by g2-g3 and e3-e4. The
active} e5 {leads to an interesting position after} 18. dxe5 fxe5 19. Nh3 $13 {
Even though the position is objectively equal, Black has a shaky centre and
slightly vulnerable king. The construction Ng5 & h6-pawn can prove dangerous
for Black in some positions.}) 16... b5 17. Qg4 b4 18. O-O {White has
completed the development and is now ready to proceed with h5-h6.} a5 ({After} 
18... f5 19. Qg3 bxc3 20. bxc3 $14 {[%cal Gh5h6] White has a slight advantage.
Besides the kingside threats created by the eventual h5-h6, Black should also
reckon with possible invasions via the b-file.}) 19. h6 g5 20. Nf3 Kf7 21. Ne2
$14 {[%cal Gb2b3,Ge3e4] Practically speaking, White is slightly better.
Depending on the concrete circumstances, White will try to open the position
with e3-e4 or b2-b3. Additionally, the black king is vulnerable.}) 14. Nxd4 e5
15. Ne6 Qc4 16. Nxf8 Bxf8 $6 {This is dubious.} ({Even after the precise} 16...
Ndc5 $1 {, however, Black does not have enough compensation for the exchange.}
17. Nxc5 Nxc5 18. Bg3 Bxf8 19. Rh4 e4 20. Qe2 Nd3+ 21. Kf1 $14 {transposes to
the game.}) 17. Bg3 Ndc5 18. Nxc5 ({Keeping the knight with} 18. Nc1 $1 $16 {
would have given White even bigger advantage. White is ready to follow with
Qe2.}) 18... Nxc5 19. Rh4 e4 20. Qe2 Nd3+ 21. Kf1 {As pointed out above,
Black's compensation is not sufficient. Later on, White managed to convert the
advantage.} f5 22. Kg1 Rc8 23. Rh1 Kf7 24. Kh2 Be7 25. a3 b5 26. Rad1 Ke6 27.
Rxd3 Qxd3 28. Qxd3 exd3 29. Rd1 Bxa3 30. bxa3 Rxc3 31. Kg1 Rxa3 32. Kf1 b4 33.
Ke1 b3 34. Kd2 b2 35. Rb1 Rb3 36. Bc7 d4 37. exd4 Kd5 38. f4 g6 39. h6 Kxd4 40.
Be5+ Ke4 41. Bxb2 Rb7 42. Re1+ Kxf4 43. Be5+ Kg4 44. Kxd3 g5 45. Bd4 Rd7 46.
Re6 Kg3 47. Rf6 Kg4 48. Ra6 f4 49. Ke4 Re7+ 50. Be5 Rb7 51. Bf6 Rb4+ 52. Bd4
Kh5 53. Rd6 Ra4 54. Kf5 Ra2 55. Bf6 Kxh6 56. Rd1 1-0

