{[%evp 0,67,28,35,24,24,24,24,24,34,25,-13,20,7,29,40,42,20,20,-10,-32,-38,2,
-15,119,54,54,25,56,0,0,182,223,184,239,256,239,240,232,264,264,245,245,245,
250,237,255,162,169,169,169,130,232,270,329,422,488,421,469,370,364,466,466,
424,469,486,574,574,691,697] The next game shows White'a attacking potential
created by the advance of the h-pawn. Even though it's a blitz game, the play
of Magnus is of a high quality.} 1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 Bd6 5.
Nbd2 O-O 6. c3 b6 7. Ne5 c5 8. Bd3 Bb7 {[%cal Gb8c6] This move indicates
Black's intention to fight for the e5-square by means of ...Nc6. It turns out,
however, that White is just in time to develop his kingside initiative.} 9. h4
Nc6 10. Qf3 {This is maybe not the most precise move since White loses his
control of the e5-square.} ({More to the point would have been} 10. h5 Qc7 11.
Ndf3 h6 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. Ne5 $14 {[%cal Gd1f3,Gf3f4,Gg2g4,Gg4g5]
with a slight advantage for White. A possible plan would be Qf3-f4 followed by
g2-g4-g5.}) 10... Rc8 $2 {Mamedyarov neglects the fight for e5 as well.} ({
Black should have taken advantage of White's inaccuracy by playing} 10... Qc7 {
Given the fast time control, I presume that in this case Carlsen would have
chosen} 11. Nxc6 Bxc6 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. h5 h6 14. g4 $13 {with a double edged
play.} ({The endgame arising after} 14. Qf4 Qxf4 15. exf4 cxd4 $1 {[%csl Rd2]
[%cal Gc8c1]} 16. cxd4 a6 17. Nf3 Bb5 18. Kd2 Bxd3 19. Kxd3 Rfc8 $11 {is equal.
})) 11. h5 h6 12. Qg3 {This was the point behind White's play. With a pawn on
h5, g3 is a perfect spot for the queen. Now, Black cannot play ...Nh5. White
has already a winning advantage.} Ne8 {This is losing on the spot.} ({More
tenacious would have been} 12... cxd4 {Even in this case, however, after} 13.
Bxh6 Ng4 14. Qxg4 Bxe5 15. exd4 f5 16. Qg6 Qf6 17. Bg5 Qxg6 18. hxg6 Bf6 19.
Nf3 $18 {White is winning.}) 13. Bxh6 cxd4 ({The alternative} 13... Bxe5 14.
dxe5 Nxe5 {does not help either. After} 15. Bc2 d4 16. Bxg7 Nxg7 17. Qxe5 $18 {
White is winning.}) 14. Bxg7 $1 {This move marks the beginning of a forced
sequence which results in a winning position for White.} Nxg7 15. h6 Qf6 16.
hxg7 Qxg7 17. Bh7+ Kh8 18. Nxf7+ Rxf7 19. Bg6+ Kg8 20. Bxf7+ Kxf7 21. Qxd6 $18
{The game is over.} dxc3 22. bxc3 Ne5 23. O-O d4 24. f3 dxe3 25. Ne4 e2 26. Rf2
Kg8 27. Qxe6+ Kh8 28. Qh3+ Kg8 29. Rxe2 Rf8 30. Qe6+ Kh8 31. Ng5 Nxf3+ 32. Nxf3
Bxf3 33. Rf2 Qxc3 34. Raf1 1-0

