{Quite often we should deal with closed positions which are typical for the
Slav Defence. Note that such positions often arise with colours reversed.
Let's take a look at a typical example.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3
Nc6 5. c3 Qb6 {We have some kind of a Slav Defence with colours reversed. Now,
Whtie should decide how to protect the b2-pawn. The most natural way to do it
is} 6. Qb3 ({Generally speaking, playing} 6. b3 $6 {is undesirable. Black can
make use of the weakened a1-h8 diagonal by playing} g6 {[%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8,
Gf6d7,Ge7e5] The idea is to prepare the advance ...e7-e5 after ...Bg7, ...0-0,
and ...Nd7.}) ({Even after} 6. Qc2 {I would suggest} g6 7. Nbd2 Bg7 8. h3 O-O
9. Be2 Bf5 {[%cal Gf6d7,Ge7e5] Once again, Black is planning to continue with .
..Nd7 followed by ...e7-e5.}) 6... c4 7. Qc2 ({The endgame arising after} 7.
Qxb6 axb6 {is dealt with in the lectures of Boris Gelfand and Davorin
Kuljasevic. In the next two examples, I will analyze the same endgame
configuration with colours reversed.}) 7... Bf5 8. Qc1 e6 ({I prefer starting
with} 8... h6 {with the idea to rule out any Nh4-based attempts.}) 9. Nbd2 h6
10. h3 Be7 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O {We have reached a very important pawn
structure. Besides having a considerable space advantage on the queenside,
Black managed to get his light-squared bishop outside of the pawn chain. His
thematic idea is to play on the queenside by means of ...b7-b5-b4. White's
only constructive plan is based on the advance e3-e4. He usually does it with
Re1 followed by the manoeuvre Bd1-c2.} Rfc8 $1 {[%cal Gb6d8,Gb7b5,Gb5b4] I
think this is the most precise move. Before playing ...Qd8 followed by pushing
the b-pawn, Black brings his rook to the queenside.} 13. Bd1 Qd8 14. Bc2 b5 $1
{This is another important moment for the understanding of the pawn structure.
Black is ready to accept the exchange on f5. We already know that doubled
pawns on the f-file provide important advantages such as better control of the
e4-square and e-file.} 15. Re1 b4 16. e4 {The most precise reaction to this
thematic advance is} dxe4 17. Nxe4 Nd5 {After the exchange on e4, the
d5-square is available for the knight. The Indian player makes use of it in
the best possible way. We can safely say that Black is already slightly better
in this position.} 18. Bd2 Rab8 19. Ng3 bxc3 20. bxc3 Bxc2 21. Qxc2 Qa5 {
Black's play is pretty straightforward. Now, he is getting ready to double the
rooks on the b-file.} 22. Re4 $2 {This move gives Black a big advantage. White
does not have attacking chances on the kingside.} Nf6 {Black tries to prevent
any counterplay.} ({Computer suggests that even more precise would be} 22...
Ba3 {[%cal Gb8b2] The point is that in the case of} 23. Rg4 {we can always play
} Nf6 $19 {[%cal Gb8b2] with ...Rb2 to follow on the next move.}) 23. Rh4 $6 {
The rooks has nothing to do here.} ({The best would have been to accept the
mistake and play} 23. Ree1 {with the idea to start fighting for the b-file.})
23... Rb5 24. Re1 Rcb8 $19 {Black is ready to invade via the b-file. White's
position is already hopeless.} 25. Ne5 Nxe5 26. dxe5 Nd7 27. Rxc4 Rb2 28. Qd1
Nxe5 29. Ra4 Qb5 30. c4 Nxc4 31. Bc3 Rb1 32. Qxb1 Qxb1 33. Rxb1 Rxb1+ 34. Kh2
Nb6 35. Nh5 Nxa4 0-1

[Event "Titled Tuesday internet op May 4th"]
[Site "chess.com INT"]
