{[%evp 0,87,31,16,16,16,16,16,34,-15,-13,-28,17,25,25,23,19,19,25,22,25,43,40,
45,17,19,9,7,30,26,26,9,47,66,54,29,18,10,33,37,38,-19,59,48,116,130,152,172,
220,219,247,261,434,463,492,553,565,565,565,480,639,529,574,642,641,663,698,
681,713,579,598,547,581,419,456,363,780,488,700,800,815,828,831,840,840,825,
1040,1399,1232,1793] The structure from the previous game often arises with
colours reversed. The next example features the positions which arise after
the exchange of the queens.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 d5 3. e3 Bf5 4. c4 e6 5. Nc3 c6
6. Qb3 Qb6 7. c5 {We see the same approach. Contrary to the previous example,
in this position, Black is forced to exchange the queens because White
controls the c7-square.} Qxb3 8. axb3 {[%cal Gb3b4,Gb4b5] The structure
arising after the recapture axb3 is almost always in White's favour. The rook
enters the game in a powerful way. White's thematic idea is b3-b4-b5. For
Black is not easy to deal with the space advantage provided by the c5-pawn.}
Nbd7 9. b4 {This is a straightforward way to play the position. I think it
works pretty well.} ({Some player prefer the cautious} 9. h3 {[%csl Gh2][%cal
Gf6h5,Gf4h2] anticipating any ...Nh5 ideas.}) 9... Nh5 {Going after the
dark-squared bishop is Black's best try. Otherwise, White will just follow
with b4-b5.} 10. Bc7 Rc8 11. Be5 $1 {This is the point. White gains an
important tempo by attacking the a7-pawn.} a6 {Black is forced to play this
move.} (11... f6 $2 {loses to} 12. Bd6 {[%cal Gf1e2,Gg2g4] when White is
planning to proceed with Be2 followed by g2-g4. It turns out that Black cannot
save the piece.}) ({After} 11... Nxe5 $2 12. dxe5 {[%cal Ga1a7,Gf1e2,Gg2g4]
White is winning again. Besides the fact that a7 is hanging, White threatens
to win a piece by means of Be2 and g2-g4.}) 12. h3 {[%cal Gg2g4]} Nhf6 13. Bh2
{White managed to save the dark-squared bishop and enjoys a huge positional
advantage.} h5 14. Nf3 Be7 15. Nd2 $1 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gd2b3,Gb3a5] Remember
this typical manoeuvre. The knight is heading to it's best square in the
structure - a5. Defending the b7-pawn becomes a major issue for Black.
Additionally, Black should be aware of different piece sacrifices on a6, b7,
and c6.} Ne4 {A logical move. By exchanging a pair of knights, Black is trying
to reduce the impact of White's space advantage.} 16. Ncxe4 Bxe4 17. Nb3 {
[%cal Gb3a5]} Bd8 18. Na5 $1 {Even though Black has taken the a5-square under
control, White should play this move. Black's problem is that after} Bxa5 19.
bxa5 {[%cal Ga1a4,Ga4b4] The structural modification is favourable for White.
Black has no reliable defence against the manoeuvre Ra4-b4.} e5 20. Ra4 exd4 $2
{This move is losing the game since the h2-bishop is already a monster.} ({
More tenacious would have been} 20... f6 {Nevertheless, after} 21. f3 Bf5 22.
Rb4 Rc7 23. Be2 $16 {White has an obvious advantage.}) 21. exd4 O-O 22. Rb4 $18
{Black is collapsing. The rest is a matter of simple technique.} Rfe8 23. Kd2
Nf8 24. Rxb7 Ne6 25. Kc3 f5 26. f3 Bb1 27. Bxa6 Ra8 28. Rb6 Ba2 29. b4 Ra7 30.
Bd3 Bc4 31. Bxc4 dxc4 32. Rxc6 f4 33. Kxc4 Rd7 34. Rxe6 Rxe6 35. Bxf4 Re2 36.
c6 Rc2+ 37. Kb5 Rxd4 38. Be3 Rd3 39. Bc5 Rd8 40. c7 Rc8 41. Kc6 Re2 42. b5 Ree8
43. b6 Ra8 44. b7 1-0

