{As pointed out in the annotations to the previous game, sometimes White opts
for a piece sacrifice on the queenside. The idea of such a sacrifice is to
create a mass of rolling advanced passed pawns. This approach is very well
illustrated in the game Grachev - Mohammad Fahad, 2016. In this position,
Grachev went for the typical} 12. Nd2 Bd8 13. Nb3 {Here, instead of castling,
Black decided to eliminate the annoying f4-bishop with} Bc7 $2 {This move,
however, runs into a typical tactical idea:} 14. Bxc7 Rxc7 15. b5 $1 {[%csl
Rh8] This move is possible due to the vulnerability of the h8-rook.} O-O 16. b6
$1 {Of course! Instead of winning a pawn and providing Black with the
semi-open b-file, White keeps winning space. Na5 on the next move will be
killing.} Rcc8 17. Na5 Rb8 18. Bxa6 $1 {This is the final touch. When our
pawns are so advanced, all kinds of piece sacrifices become possible.} bxa6 19.
Nxc6 Rb7 20. Ne7+ Kh8 21. Nxf5 exf5 22. Rxa6 $18 {White's pawns are
unstoppable. Grachev converted his advantage in a few moves.} Ne4 23. Nxe4 fxe4
24. Kd2 Nb8 25. Ra8 Kg8 26. Rha1 Nc6 27. Kc3 f5 28. b4 Kf7 29. Rxf8+ Kxf8 30.
b5 Nd8 31. Ra7 Rb8 32. Kb4 Ke8 33. Rxg7 1-0

