{[%evp 0,82,29,29,27,28,28,20,32,25,60,-17,23,23,40,31,50,-29,41,7,6,8,20,17,
17,11,16,16,10,0,25,23,21,22,23,22,16,26,17,0,12,14,14,15,13,6,17,24,21,26,29,
10,39,37,24,28,8,8,14,55,52,52,0,0,0,24,11,10,18,18,18,67,99,91,111,101,112,
112,208,173,983,1014,1054,1076,1076] At the end of the lecture, we shall take
a look at the Exchange Caro-Kann structure. In most of the cases, this
structure arises via the following move order:} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 c5
4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 cxd4 6. exd4 {In comparison to the Exchange Variation in
Caro-Kann, in this line Black usually manages to get his bishop to f5. With a
black bishop on f5, White's kingside attack is not so fast. Before starting
active actions on the kingside, White usually tries to restrict Black's
queenside play. In order to do so, White often pushes his a-pawn all the way
to a5. Being on b3, the knight supports the advance of the pawn. Once this
idea achieved, White can slowly start combining his kingside play with
pressure along the e-file. We shall take a look at two model games. The first
one is Carlsen - Kramnik, 2019.} Qb6 7. Nb3 {This is the traditional way of
dealing with ...Qb6. As pointed out in the introduction, the knight is well
placed on b3.} Bf5 8. Be2 e6 9. O-O Be7 10. a4 $1 {[%cal Ga4a5,Ga5a6] It's
important to remember this thematic idea. The positional threat is a4-a5-a6.
In this way, White provokes the advance ...a7-a6.} a6 11. a5 Qd8 12. Ne5 {
We can now see the benefit of provoking the move ...a7-a6. Since the queenside
is now locked, Black has no counterplay. White can start gradually preparing
his kingside play.} Rc8 13. c3 O-O 14. Re1 Ne4 15. Bd3 {White is slowly
improving his pieces. On the other hand, Black's counterplay is not obvious at
all. Once his active pieces exchanged, Kramnik will run out of resources.} Nxe5
16. Bxe5 Bg6 17. Bf4 Nd6 18. Bxg6 {In this structure, exchanging the
light-squared bishops on g6 is favourable for White. Later, the g6-pawn could
be used as a hook by means of h2-h4-h5.} hxg6 19. Bxd6 $1 {A very instructive
moment. Carlsen eliminates Black's only active pieces. Given the static pawn
structure, the tandem queen + knight is better than queen + bishop.} Bxd6 20.
g3 {[%cal Gb3c1,Gc1d3,Gg1g2,Gh2h4,Gh4h5,Ge1h1] White's plan is fairly simple.
After transferring the knight to d3, he will start attacking on the kingside
by means of Kg2 followed by h2-h4-h5. Black does not have enough resources to
counter this plan.} b5 {This is already desperation. Black accepts clearly
inferior pawn structure in order to create at least some counterplay.} 21. axb6
Qxb6 22. Re2 {[%cal Gb3c1,Gc1d3,Ge2b2] Since the b2-pawn is safely protected,
White is now ready to reroute his knight to d3.} Rb8 23. Nc1 a5 24. Nd3 Qb5 25.
h4 $1 {It's time to start the attack.} Rfc8 26. Rd2 Ra8 27. h5 gxh5 28. Qxh5 {
White's attack is very dangerous from a practical point of view. Despite some
inaccuracies (normal for a blitz game), Carlsen managed to win the game.} g6
29. Qh6 a4 30. Kg2 Bf8 31. Qf4 Bg7 32. Ne5 Qe8 33. Rd3 f6 34. Ng4 Qf8 35. Rf3
a3 36. bxa3 f5 37. Qg5 Kf7 38. Rh1 Rxa3 39. Rh7 Rcxc3 40. Nh6+ Ke8 41. Qxg6+
Kd8 1-0

