{[%evp 0,55,29,29,27,7,20,20,60,9,28,23,33,33,33,19,21,19,19,-16,-34,-36,-36,
-42,-40,-39,-32,-46,-33,-37,-29,-21,-21,-21,-24,-21,-27,-61,22,0,45,48,73,73,
77,56,159,154,262,262,278,278,331,345,438,462,462,478] We will finish the
lecture with a model game played by the young Indian talent Raunak Sadhwani.} 
1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 d5 3. e3 c5 4. c3 Nc6 ({The idea of White's move order is to
meet} 4... Qb6 {with} 5. Qb3 {Now, after} c4 6. Qc2 {, Black cannot play} Bf5
$4 {due to the unprotected c8-square.} 7. Qxf5 Qxb2 8. Qc8#) 5. Nd2 cxd4 6.
exd4 {We have finally a typical Exchange Caro-Kann structure. Now, Black's
most reliable choice is} Bf5 ({With a pawn on c3, the move} 6... Qb6 {is well
met by} 7. Qb3 {In this case, Black should always reckon with the idea of Qxb6
followed by Bc7. Note that the structure arising after} Qxb3 8. axb3 {is
favourable for White since the a1-rook is already very active. Furthermore,
White can gain additional space on the queenside by means of b3-b4-b5.}) 7.
Ngf3 e6 8. Qb3 Bd6 {This dynamic pawn sacrifice is Black's most precise
reaction.} ({The most common} 8... Qc8 {is a bit passive. White's best bet on
advantage is to go after the bishop pair by playing} 9. Nh4 Be4 {Trying to
provoke the weakening f2-f3 before playing ...Bg6.} ({After} 9... Bg4 10. h3
Bh5 11. g4 Bg6 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. Bg2 $14 {White's bishop pair provides a
slight but stable plus.}) {I think that at this point White should continue}
10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. g3 $1 {[%cal Gh4g2] Making the g2-square available for the
knight. After a few normal moves such as} Be7 12. Ng2 Nd5 13. Bd2 O-O 14. Be2
Qd7 15. O-O $14 {[%cal Ga1e1,Gf2f3] the position is already stable. The
asymmetric pawn structure makes the bishop pair potentially dangerous.
Furthermore, White has an easy way to improve his position - Rae1 followed by
f2-f3.}) 9. Bxd6 {The most solid approach to the position.} ({Practice has
shown that after} 9. Qxb7 Bxf4 10. Qxc6+ Kf8 {Black has enough compensation.})
9... Qxd6 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O {Even though Black's position looks pretty solid,
it's not easy for him to find a plan. The minority attack never works when
White has a bishop on the diagonal f1-a6 and the move a2-a4 is included. On
the other hand, opting for ...e6-e5 would lead to a passive position with IQP.
At the same time, White can slowly mount his pressure on the kingside.} Rab8
12. a4 h6 13. Rfe1 Rfc8 14. Bf1 {The construction Re1&Bf1 works very well in
such positions. All White pieces are perfectly coordinated. At the same time,
White has firm control of the important squares e5 and b5.} Nd7 15. a5 {
I think that this makes easier the advance ...b7-b5. In general, I suggest
playing a4-a5 only when Black has committed to ...a7-a6.} ({Maybe White should
have adopted the approach of Carlsen -} 15. Qd1 Qc7 16. Nb3 {restricting
Black's queenside play. White can already consider slowly advancing on the
kingside.}) 15... b5 16. axb6 Rxb6 17. Qa2 a5 {Black has a decent counterplay
on the a-file.} 18. Rec1 Ra8 $2 {This mistake is typical for blitz.} ({Black
should have gained more space on the queenside by playing} 18... a4 $1 {
[%csl Rb2]}) 19. b4 $1 $16 {White is already clearly better. After some more
inaccuracies, Raunak converted his advantage.} Rab8 20. bxa5 Rb2 21. Qa3 Qc7
22. c4 dxc4 23. Nxc4 R2b3 24. Qd6 Qxd6 25. Nxd6 Nb4 26. a6 Bc2 27. a7 Ra8 28.
Nb5 1-0

