{[%evp 0,116,19,31,14,30,23,29,35,32,58,63,31,21,33,33,48,47,39,32,21,31,68,7,
20,3,0,-11,2,9,0,-30,-11,-15,-17,-16,-4,-23,-25,-23,-13,-34,-39,-40,-54,-59,
-37,-59,-26,-48,-39,-39,-29,-67,-14,-10,16,-25,-44,-79,-77,-171,-169,-172,-165,
-234,-210,-200,-206,-222,-173,-169,-171,-171,-167,-175,-165,-197,-176,-213,
-214,-253,-245,-277,-254,-256,-207,-222,-213,-262,-237,-244,-236,-295,-279,
-276,-279,-285,-285,-305,-291,-291,-303,-421,-281,-291,-281,-300,-300,-307,
-305,-308,-287,-290,-333,-409,-417,-472,-482]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 {
Gata Kamsky is a specialist in the London system. He has employed it quite
often from his childhood.} c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Bb5 {A rare option, probably a bit
premature at this point because Black can force the knight to c3 with a check.}
({The main move here is} 5. Nbd2) 5... cxd4 ({It was also possible to play} 
5... Qa5+ 6. Nc3 Ne4 {but during the game I was not sure about the position
arising after} 7. O-O Nxc3 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. bxc3 Qxc3 {I win a pawn, but he
might get good compensation for it after} 10. Ne5 {since my pieces are
undeveloped. After} g6 {it is a game.}) 6. exd4 ({My point was that if he takes
} 6. Nxd4 {then I play} Bd7 {and keep developing normally.}) 6... Qa5+ 7. Nc3 {
The knight is not placed so well on c3 in this type of position. In fact, after
} Bg4 {we get a position that is very similar to one variation of the Ragozin
defence with colours reversed. In that variation, the knight on c6 is also not
placed well and Black wants to transfer it somewhere else and play ...c6 (in
this case, c3). The game continued normally:} 8. O-O e6 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 {
With the knight on d2 and pawn on c3, we would have a typical London system
position that is popular nowadays. White has the bishop pair and typically can
claim a slight edge, although there is also nothing wrong with the black
position. Here, however, things are different since White does not have such a
harmonious setup.} Rc8 {I wanted to make sure that White does not force me to
take on c6 with a pawn. I like this pawn structure for Black.} ({In the event
of} 10... Be7 {White would maybe have an option to go} 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. b3
O-O 13. Na4 $11 {which still looks equal, but less flexible than the game
continuation.}) (10... Qb4 11. Rfd1) 11. Rfd1 Be7 (11... Bb4 12. Bf1 Bxc3 13.
bxc3) 12. Bf1 O-O {[#] What would you play here as White? It is an instructive
moment.} 13. Ne2 $1 {This is the best plan - White should ask himself, what is
my worst placed piece? The knight makes way for the pawn to advance to c3,
while also looking for a better square itself.} (13. a3 {/\Ne2,c3,Nc1}) (13. g4
{is a tempting plan, but a bit premature because White is not solid enough in
the centre.}) 13... b5 {Minority attack is logical.} 14. c3 (14. a3 {seems
more precise. If} Qb6 15. c3 Na5 16. Nc1 {then his knight gets to a good
square d3 and he has a solid position.}) 14... b4 15. Qd3 Qb6 (15... Ne4 16. c4
) 16. cxb4 (16. c4 dxc4 17. Qxc4 Nd5) 16... Nxb4 17. Qb3 Ne4 {[#] This is a
critical position for White. He made an inaccurate move} 18. a3 ({However, he
should have challenged the knight on e4 with} 18. Nc3 $1 Bd6 19. Be3 $11 {
With a roughly balanced position. if} Nxc3 20. bxc3 {the pawn on c3 is not so
bad at all, it can always move to c4 if needed.} Nc6 21. Qxb6 axb6 22. Rab1 Bc7
23. c4) 18... Nc6 19. Qxb6 axb6 {White is positionally worse here. He has an
isolated pawn on d4 and several weak squares on the queenside. I planned to go
...Na5 to start exploiting these weaknesses, so he played} 20. b4 ({Maybe he
should have exchanged the rooks:} 20. Rac1 Na5 21. Rxc8 Rxc8 22. Rc1 $15 {
as suggested by Y.Yakovich, although the arising endgame is still easier to
play for Black.}) 20... g5 $1 {I believe that this is a strong idea. The pawn
on g5 will not be weak and it was important to secure d6-square for the knight.
} 21. Be3 (21. Bh2 Bd6) 21... Nd6 {Now we can reroute the knight to a great
outpost on c4.} 22. Nc1 f5 {Black is very comfortable and has a choice of
promising plans.} ({It was also possible to play immediately} 22... Nc4 $5 23.
Bxc4 dxc4 24. Ne2 Bf6 25. Rac1 Ne7 $15) 23. Nb3 (23. f4 $5) 23... Nc4 24. b5
Nd8 {This was a big mistake. I thought that I should not exchange a pair of
knights.} ({I should have played} 24... N6a5 $1 $17 25. Nxa5 Nxa5 {with a
serious advantage. The knight hits several important squares from a5 and White
has weak pawns on a3, d4, etc.}) 25. a4 Nb7 26. Bc1 f4 {[#] Another poor
decision. I wanted to go ...Nb7-d6-f5, but this move contains a clear weakness.
How can White take advantage of this?} ({A better option was} 26... Bf6 $17)
27. Be2 {Now g4-square is available to the bishop.} Bb4 28. Ra2 {A mistake by
Gata.} ({He should have continued} 28. Bg4 $1 Rf6 29. Bd2 $11 {to trade of my
strong bishop on b4.}) 28... Nbd6 29. Bd3 $2 {White is starting to collapse.
He should have tried to exchange bishops on d2 anyway.} Ra8 {Now Nxb5 is a
threat. White pieces are very poorly placed.} 30. Kf1 {This just loses.} ({
A better resistance would have been offered with} 30. Bd2 Bxd2 31. Nxd2 Nxd2
32. Rdxd2 Rfc8 $17) 30... Nxb5 31. Rc2 Nbd6 32. Bd2 Rxa4 33. Bxb4 Rxb4 $19 {
With two extra pawns, Black is completely winning.} 34. Nc1 Nf5 $6 35. Bxf5
Rxf5 36. Nd3 Rb3 37. Ra2 Rf7 38. Ke2 Nd6 39. Rda1 (39. Ne5 Rc7) 39... Nb5 (
39... f3+ 40. gxf3 Nb5 41. Ke3 Rf4) 40. Kd2 Nxd4 41. Rc1 Rb5 42. Rc8+ Rf8 43.
Rc7 Ra5 44. Rb2 Rf7 45. Rc8+ Kg7 46. Ne5 (46. Rxb6 Ra2+ 47. Kd1 Rfa7) 46... Rb7
47. h4 gxh4 48. Rb4 Ra2+ 49. Kd3 Nf5 50. Rxf4 Rba7 51. Rc3 R7a3 52. Rxa3 Rxa3+
53. Ke2 b5 54. Rg4+ Kf6 55. Nd3 Ra8 56. Kd2 e5 57. Rb4 e4 58. Nc5 Rg8 0-1

