{[%evp 0,72,19,31,25,27,24,21,31,23,68,24,20,40,25,-64,-64,-55,-40,-31,-21,-27,
-29,-32,-23,-24,-33,-34,-43,-35,-23,-28,-28,-38,-28,-23,-18,-23,-27,-6,-1,-6,
-6,-26,-16,-17,-20,-32,0,1,-6,-2,0,0,20,18,17,8,12,8,0,0,0,-98,-93,-147,-147,
-146,-135,-112,-154,-156,-156,-156,-47]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 {
My tournament situation allowed me to play safely for a draw, but I approached
it as any other normal game.} 4. e3 Nc6 5. c3 {This is not such a precise move
order.} Qb6 6. Qb3 c4 {White's idea is to provoke this move and then retreat
with the queen.} 7. Qc2 Bf5 8. Qc1 {Even though there is no more tension in
the centre, I don't think that pushing c4 is bad for Black at all - he has a
very good pawn structure and space advantage.} h6 {Just to be sure that the
bishop can retreat to h7 if attacked by the knight.} 9. h3 e6 10. Nbd2 Be7 11.
Be2 (11. b3 {is never a threat because of a tactical idea} Qa5 $1 ({I can also
simply take} 11... cxb3 12. axb3 O-O {and White will hardly be in time to
improve his knight with b4, Nb3-c5 because Black has better development and
can create counterplay with Rfc8, etc.}) 12. a4 (12. bxc4 {runs into} Ba3)
12... cxb3 13. Nxb3 Qd8 {and it is a good position for Black since there is a
backward pawn on the c-file. Because of the pawn on a4, any time White plays
c3-c4, he creates a big weakness on b4-square.}) 11... Qd8 ({Maybe a more
clever way for Black is to play} 11... O-O 12. O-O Rfc8 {as prophylaxis
against b2-b3, and only then to go 13...Qd8, 14...b5, etc.}) 12. Ne5 ({A
thematic positional idea for White is} 12. O-O O-O 13. Bd1 {but it is nothing
dramatic for Black. He continues} b5 14. Bc2 Rc8 15. Ne5 Bxc2 16. Nxc6 Rxc6 17.
Qxc2 b4 {with an initiative on the queenside.}) 12... Nxe5 13. Bxe5 O-O 14. O-O
b5 15. Re1 {Getting ready to push e4.} Ne4 {I had nothing against simplifying
the game a bit.} ({Perhaps it was more accurate to ignore White's plans in the
centre and just focus on queenside play with} 15... a5 16. Bf3 (16. Bd1 b4)
16... Bd3 17. e4 b4) 16. Bf3 Ng5 17. Bd1 Bd6 {Once more, the idea is to
simplify. It is not so much that the white bishop is too strong as the fact
that d6 is a very comfortable square for the queen.} 18. Bxd6 Qxd6 19. Bc2 Bxc2
20. Qxc2 f5 {This way, I am making sure that White never plays e3-e4 since
f2-f3 weakens his king too much. Black has a very comfortable position. My
opponent decided to open the b-file with} 21. b3 Rfc8 22. bxc4 bxc4 23. Qa4 Ne4
{A decent move, but from here on, I began playing inaccurately.} ({The
simplest was} 23... Rab8 $1 24. Reb1 (24. Rab1 a6) 24... a6 {protecting
everything} 25. a3 f4 {and only Black can be slightly better here.}) 24. Nxe4
fxe4 25. Reb1 Rc7 $6 {Suddenly, I decided to be aggressive and to go for a
counterattack on the f-file.} ({Better was} 25... Rcb8 $1 {and if} 26. Rxb8+
Qxb8 27. Qc6 Qc8 28. Qxc8+ Rxc8 $11 {the rook endgame is completely fine as I
will go ...Rc6-a6 with counterplay against white pawns.}) 26. Rb5 Rf8 27. Rab1
Rcf7 28. R1b2 Kh7 29. Qb4 Qd8 30. a4 {[#] This is actually a mistake. How can
Black take advantage of it?} ({White could have forced a rook endgame with} 30.
Rb8 Qxb8 31. Qxb8 Rxb8 32. Rxb8 {Most likely this is a draw because Black has
no real weaknesses.} Kg6 33. Kf1 Kf6 34. Ke2 Rd7 35. a4 $5 $14 (35. Rb5 Rd6 36.
a4 Rb6) (35. f3 exf3+ 36. Kxf3 Rd6)) 30... a5 $1 $19 {It is important to
distract white pieces from the b-file before playing Qh4.} (30... Qh4 {is not
so good because White plays} 31. Rb8 $1 {and it is not possible to take on f2.}
a5 32. Qxf8 Rxf8 33. Rxf8 Qe7 34. Ra8 Qa3 35. Rb7 $18) 31. Rxa5 Qh4 32. Qd6
Rxf2 33. Rxf2 Qxf2+ (33... Rxf2 34. Ra7 Re2 $19) 34. Kh2 Rf6 35. Qg3 Qd2 36.
Ra8 {Here, my opponent offered a draw which meant resigning the match, so I
accepted for practical reasons. Black is winning with 36...Qxc3.} Rg6 (36...
Qxc3 37. a5 Qc1 38. Qb8 Qxe3) (36... Rg6 37. Rh8+ Kxh8 38. Qxg6 Qxe3 39. h4 $1
$11 (39. Qxe6 Qf4+ 40. Kg1 e3) (39. Qg3 Qc1 40. a5 e3 41. Qe5 Qxc3 42. a6 $17))
1/2-1/2

