1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 {This is the most accurate
move order.} cxd4 {I took here to determine the pawn structure, so that I can
safely develop the bishop to f5.} (5... Bf5 {is strongly met by} 6. dxc5 {
and it is not so easy to get the pawn back.} Qa5 7. Nd4) ({A very recent game
from Wijk aan Zee continued:} 5... Bg4 6. c3 e6 7. Qb3 Qc8 8. h3 Bh5 9. Be2 Be7
10. O-O O-O 11. Qd1 Nd7 $11 {1-0 (49) Giri,A (2764)-Wojtaszek,R (2705) Wijk
aan Zee 2021 This looks like a very playable position for both sides, though
somehow Giri managed to outplay Wojtaszek.}) ({Another important game from
previus year saw:} 5... Nh5 $5 {A creative idea of Daniil Dubov - he
sacrificed a pawn and quickly obtained active play for it:} 6. dxc5 Nxf4 7.
exf4 g6 8. c3 Bg7 9. Bb5 O-O 10. O-O d4 11. Bxc6 dxc3 $1 {This intermediate
move is the key, so Black soon equalized.} 12. Be4 cxd2 13. Qxd2 Qxd2 14. Nxd2
Bxb2 15. Rab1 Ba3 16. c6 {1/2-1/2 (16) Firouzja,A (2723)-Dubov,D (2683) Wijk
aan Zee 2020}) 6. exd4 Bf5 {For many year this was considered as comfortable
main line for Black, but recently White found some new ideas to pose problems.}
7. c3 ({One of these ideas is} 7. Bb5 Rc8 (7... e6 8. Ne5 Qb6 9. c4 dxc4 10.
Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Ndxc4 Qa6 12. Qe2 Bb4+ 13. Bd2 Bxd2+ 14. Nxd2 Qb5 15. Nb3 O-O
16. Rc1 Rfc8 17. Rxc6 Qa4 18. Rxc8+ Rxc8 19. O-O Qxa2 20. Nc5 Qd5 21. Qa6 Rf8
22. Nc6 Kh8 23. b4 Ne4 24. Rc1 Ng5 25. h4 Nh3+ 26. Kf1 Nf4 27. f3 Bh3 28. gxh3
Qxf3+ 29. Ke1 Qe3+ 30. Kd1 Qxh3 31. Kc2 Qxh4 32. Kb1 Qf2 33. Rc2 Qg1+ 34. Ka2
h5 35. Qxa7 Qg3 36. b5 Nd5 37. b6 Qd6 38. Nd3 Qg3 39. Nde5 f6 40. b7 fxe5 41.
b8=Q Rxb8 42. Qxb8+ Kh7 43. Qxe5 Qf3 44. Qxe6 Nc3+ 45. Rxc3 Qxc3 46. Qf5+ Kh6
47. d5 h4 48. Ne5 Qd2+ 49. Ka3 Qe3+ 50. Kb2 Qd2+ 51. Ka3 Qe3+ 52. Kb4 Qd4+ 53.
Ka3 Qe3+ 54. Ka2 Qd2+ 55. Kb1 Qd1+ 56. Kb2 Qd2+ 57. Ka3 Qe3+ 58. Kb4 Qd4+ 59.
Nc4 g5 60. d6 g4 61. d7 h3 62. Qf8+ {1-0 (62) Aronian,L (2775) -Inarkiev,E 
(2663) Moscow 2019}) 8. c3 e6 9. Qe2 Nd7 10. h4 a6 11. Bd3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Be7
13. Kf1 Qb6 14. Rb1 Qb5 15. Qxb5 axb5 16. a3 h5 17. Nb3 f6 18. Re1 Kf7 19. Nc1
Nf8 20. Nd3 Ng6 21. Bg3 Na5 22. Kg1 Nc4 23. Re2 Rhe8 24. Kh2 Bf8 25. Rhe1 b6
26. Kg1 Ra8 27. Bf4 Rac8 28. g3 Rc6 29. Kg2 Be7 30. Ng1 Bf8 31. Nh3 Be7 32. Ng1
Bf8 33. Nf3 Be7 34. Kh3 Ra8 35. Bc1 Re8 36. g4 hxg4+ 37. Kxg4 Rh8 38. h5 Nf8
39. Nf4 Bd8 40. Rh1 Rg8 41. Nh4 Bc7 42. Nfg6 Nd7 43. Rhe1 Re8 44. Bf4 Bxf4 45.
Nxf4 Rd6 46. Kh3 Nf8 47. Nfg6 Nh7 48. f4 Rdd8 49. Rg1 Nd6 50. Reg2 Rg8 51. Ne7
Ng5+ 52. fxg5 Kxe7 53. gxf6+ Kxf6 54. Rg6+ Kf7 55. Nf3 Rdf8 56. Ne5+ Ke7 57.
Rxg7+ Rxg7 58. Rxg7+ Kf6 59. h6 Rh8 60. Kg4 Rxh6 61. Rd7 {1-0 (61) Firouzja,A 
(2749)-Anton Guijarro,D (2679) Wijk aan Zee 2021}) 7... e6 8. Nh4 {White tries
to win the bishop pair.} (8. Qb3 {was considered to be the principled move
before, when 8...Qc8 would be met by 9.Nh4. However, an important idea for
Black is:} Bd6 $1 {I prepared this novelty many years ago, but unfortunately
no one played London against me then. Suddenly, Alexey Shirov played this in
front of me in the same tournament in which I participated!} 9. Qxb7 ({The
idea is that after} 9. Bxd6 Qxd6 10. Qxb7 Rb8 11. Qa6 Rb6 12. Qa4 O-O $17 {
Black has a huge initiative on the b-file.}) 9... Bxf4 10. Qxc6+ Kf8 {Bishops
are strong, Black king can be moved to g7 and Black can put a lot of pressure
on the b-file.} 11. g3 Bxd2+ 12. Nxd2 g6 13. Bg2 Kg7 14. O-O Qb8 15. Nb3 a5 16.
Rfe1 h5 17. Nc5 h4 18. b3 hxg3 19. hxg3 Ng4 20. Qb7 Qd6 21. Qd7 Qb6 22. Qb7 Qd6
23. Qd7 Qb6 24. Qb7 {1/2-1/2 (24) Artemiev,V (2653) -Shirov,A (2673) Moscow
2016}) 8... Bg4 9. Qb3 Bd6 $1 {This idea comes in even better circumstances
now.} 10. Bxd6 (10. Qxb7 Bxf4 11. Qxc6+ Kf8 {is a better version of 9.Qb3 Bd6
line since the knight is poorly placed on h4.}) 10... Qxd6 11. h3 Bh5 12. Bd3 {
Castling kingside is possible, but I decided to play originally:} O-O-O {
I am not sure if it is so strong objectively, but it is a reasonable move. My
logic was that my king would be safe on b8, while if he castles kingside, I
could attack him with ...g5-g4 because of a small weakness on h3.} 13. Bb5 (13.
Nhf3 e5) 13... Kb8 14. Nhf3 Bxf3 {I wanted to secure e4-outpost for the knight
with this exchange.} 15. Nxf3 Ne4 {Now, White cannot castle long any more, so
he has to play} 16. O-O g5 {This was my idea.} 17. Rfe1 Rhg8 18. c4 {White
needs to create counterplay in the center.} f6 {I think that this is a good
move to solidify my pawn formation and limit f3-knight. 19...g4 is already a
threat.} 19. Bxc6 Qxc6 20. Rac1 g4 {The game is getting sharp.} (20... Qd7 21.
c5) 21. cxd5 {[#] The second question: What is the best for Black here?} (21.
hxg4 Rxg4 22. cxd5 {[#] The first question: What was my intention in this
position?} Rdg8 $1 {A very strong intermediate move.} 23. g3 (23. dxc6 Rxg2+
24. Kh1 (24. Kf1 Rxf2#) 24... Nxf2#) 23... Qd6 24. Rc2 exd5 $19 {with
unstoppable sacrifice on g3.}) 21... gxf3 {A very tempting move, but White has
a defence.} ({This is a stronger move.} 21... gxh3 $1 22. g3 {This is the only
defence.} ({The point being} 22. dxc6 Rxg2+ 23. Kf1 Rxf2+ 24. Kg1 Rg2+ 25. Kf1
Ng3#) (22. Nh4 Qxd5 23. Qxh3 Qxd4 $19) 22... Qxd5 (22... Qd6 {does not work
this time because of} 23. Rxe4 Rxg3+ 24. Kh1 $18) 23. Qxd5 exd5 {but we have
an extra pawn in a better endgame.} 24. Re2 f5 (24... Rc8 25. Rxc8+ Rxc8 26.
Kh2 $15) 25. Kh2 f4 26. gxf4 Rdf8 27. Rg1 $15) 22. Qxf3 Ng5 23. dxc6 Nxf3+ 24.
Kh1 {and now I cannot take on e1, so we enter a drawn rook endgame.} Rxd4 (
24... Nxe1 $2 25. c7+ Kc8 26. cxd8=R+ Kxd8 27. Rxe1 $16) 25. gxf3 e5 26. Rc2
Rd3 27. cxb7 Rxf3 28. Kh2 Kxb7 29. Re4 Rf5 30. Rb4+ Ka8 31. Rg4 Rxg4 32. hxg4
Rg5 33. f3 h5 34. Kh3 hxg4+ 35. fxg4 f5 36. gxf5 Rxf5 37. Re2 Rg5 38. Kh4 Rg8
39. Rxe5 Rg2 40. Rb5 1/2-1/2

