{[%evp 0,120,19,31,25,27,29,29,27,20,28,31,75,43,47,26,30,0,11,-19,22,-15,-15,
-20,29,1,26,27,31,25,29,-3,6,-45,-32,-45,-12,-16,-15,-18,-16,-25,-31,-31,-2,
-56,-34,-34,-43,-15,-25,-22,-34,-40,-33,-43,-33,-88,-13,-81,-54,-40,-28,-57,
-53,-50,-66,-66,-73,-75,-40,-52,-28,-97,-1,-47,-1,-24,-30,-152,-113,-103,-73,
-231,-93,-123,9,-58,-58,-105,-78,-70,-59,-352,-25,-109,-62,-64,-109,-66,6,15,7,
0,0,0,23,14,3,0,0,9,0,0,0,0,7,0,35,43,49,34,43]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 c5
4. e3 cxd4 {Normally, I play 2...d5 against the London system, but for this
game I decided to follow the idea of Peter Leko to play a flexible Queen's
Indian setup. I wanted to determine the pawn structure as soon as possible.} ({
In his game against Kramnik, Leko started with} 4... b6 {but this also gives
some extra options to White. Anyway, Kramnik played the normal setup with
White:} 5. Nbd2 Bb7 6. Bd3 Be7 7. h3 O-O 8. O-O {and here Leko took on d4} cxd4
9. exd4 {when we get more or less a transposition into my game against Nabaty.}
Ba6 $5 {This may look like a strange decision considering that Black has
already played with his bishop, but the point is clear - White cannot avoid
exchange of bishops. Bd3 is important for kingside attack and Black is ready
to spend a tempo to exchange it.} 10. Nc4 ({If} 10. c4 {there is} d5 {when Nd2
is not placed so well.}) 10... Qc8 11. Ne3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Nc6 13. c3 d5 {
Finally, a typical London structure, Carlsbad reversed, is achieved. The
absence of light-squared bishops is in Black's favor. This is an important
strategic point since Bd3 is usually a strong piece that can play on both
sides of the board, whereas Bc8/b7 is blocked by the pawn chain e6-d5.} 14.
Rae1 Qb7 {Black's main idea is to prepare minority attack. Kramnik, in turn,
tried to generate some play on the kingside.} 15. Ne5 Rac8 16. a3 Rfe8 17. N3g4
Ne4 $5 {Another nice maneuver that seemingly loses a tempo, but more
importantly, forces weakening of White's position. By provoking} 18. f3 {
Black diminishes opponent's attacking chances (Qg3, for example, is not
possible any more).} Nf6 19. Nxc6 Qxc6 {Black has a solid position and the
game eventually ended in a draw. 1/2-1/2 (56) Kramnik,V (2777)-Leko,P (2707)
Skopje 2015}) 5. exd4 b6 6. Bb5 {Tamir decided to play sharply. The point
behind this move is to discourage 6...Ba6.} ({It is more common to play} 6. Bd3
Be7 7. O-O O-O {when we would get a kind of position that happened in
Kramnik-Leko.}) ({Here is another game of Peter Leko that serves as a good
model for such positions:} 6. c4 Be7 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Be2 Bb7 9. O-O d5 {This
move is played more or less always when White goes c4 in the London system
since it usually leads to a good isolated queen's pawn middlegame for Black.}
10. Rc1 dxc4 11. Bxc4 Nc6 $11 {White pieces are not placed in the most
aggressive way and Black is quite comfortable.} 12. a3 Bd6 13. Bg5 h6 14. Bxf6
Qxf6 15. Ne4 Qf4 16. Nxd6 Qxd6 17. d5 exd5 18. Bxd5 Rad8 19. Bxc6 Bxc6 20. Qxd6
Rxd6 21. Rfd1 Rfd8 22. Rxd6 Rxd6 23. Ne5 Be8 24. h4 h5 25. Rc7 f6 26. Nc4 Rc6
27. Rxc6 Bxc6 28. f4 Kf7 29. Kf2 Ke6 {1/2-1/2 (29) Vazquez Igarza,R (2577)
-Leko,P (2699) Gallipoli 2017}) 6... Be7 ({If} 6... Ba6 {White would play} 7.
a4 {when the exchange of the bishops would be done in a better version for
White.} Bxb5 8. axb5 {The pawn is very strong on b5, limiting Nb8 and putting
pressure on the a-file.}) ({And if I would play} 6... a6 {then the bishop
returns to} 7. Bd3 {and I cannot exchange the bishops on a6 any more.}) 7. O-O
({Another interesting game in this line was:} 7. h3 O-O 8. O-O Bb7 {Leko
switched his concept, realizing that 8...Ba6 is strongly met by 9.a4.} 9. Re1
d6 10. a4 {Grischuk makes a useful move, hoping to exploit some queenside
weaknesses (b6-pawn) after 10...a6. However, Leko played a good maneuver,
which I also used in my game against Nabaty:} Na6 $5 11. Na3 Nc7 12. Bf1 a6 {
As a result, we got a kind of a Hedgehog with the knight on c7 instead of d7.
On the first glance, the knight might seem badly placed on this square, but we
will see that this is not the case - in this and also in my game.} 13. Rc1 Rc8
14. c4 {Grischuk was trying to increase his space advantage.} a5 $1 {An
important idea - the knight can be transferred to b4-outpost.} (14... d5 {
would be met by} 15. c5 {and White has a pawn majority on the queenside.}) 15.
Qb3 Na6 16. Nb5 Nb4 $11 {Black has no problems whatsoever and Grischuk decided
to force a draw with} 17. Na7 Ra8 18. Nb5 Rc8 19. Na7 Ra8 20. Nb5 {1/2-1/2 (20)
Grischuk,A (2785)-Leko,P (2679) Heraklion 2017}) 7... O-O 8. a4 Na6 9. Na3 Bb7
10. Re1 Nc7 11. Bd3 a6 {I decided to play this move to limit activity of Na3 -
it cannot go to b5 now and if it goes to c4 instead, I always have Ncd5.} ({
The alternative was} 11... Ncd5 12. Bd2 Nb4 {but White can simply tuck away
his bishops} 13. Bf1 Ne4 14. Bc1) 12. h3 d6 {This position is very similar to
Grischuk-Leko. The knight is very flexible on c7 - it can go to d5 in some
cases or to b4 in case of c2-c4.} 13. Rc1 {This is also similar to what
Grischuk did.} (13. Qe2 Ncd5 14. Bd2 Nh5 {and knights prepare to land on f4.})
(13. c4 d5 (13... a5 $5 {[%cal Gc7a6,Ga6b4]})) 13... Re8 {A useful move.} 14.
c3 {This is the first deviation from Grischuk-Leko and it was the first moment
in the game where I had to stop and think. Black has a solid position, yet it
is important to come up with a plan to move forward.} ({In case of} 14. c4 {
an additional option for Black is the pawn sacrifice:} e5 $5 ({Of course,} 
14... a5 {as Leko played, is simple and good.} 15. Nb1 Na6 16. Nc3 Nb4 17. Bb1
g6) (14... d5 $2 15. c5) 15. dxe5 dxe5 16. Bxe5 Bb4 {Black activates all his
pieces.} 17. Bc3 Bxc3 18. Rxc3 Rxe1+ 19. Nxe1 Ne6 20. Nac2 Nc5 {with a strong
positional compensation for the pawn.}) 14... h6 {This way, I eliminated the
Bg5 option.} ({The most natural move is} 14... Bf8 {but here White can use a
disadvantage of knight's position on c7 with} 15. Bg5 h6 16. Bh4 {and the pin
is more unpleasant than usual when the knight is on d7. I can always go back
to e7, but this seemed a bit strange. Another possible continuation was} Ncd5
17. Qd2 Ne7 $5 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. Be4 Bxe4 20. Rxe4 Bg7 21. Rh4 $5) (14... Qd7 {
preparing ...b6-b5 (with ...Bc6 if necessary, also to hint at vulnerability of
a4-pawn), is another option. Here we see another upside of knight's position
on c7. If Black could put the pawn on b5 and play Ncd5, he would achieve more
or less an ideal position in this structure.}) {My opponent is a very
aggressive attacking player, so he prepared kingside attack with} 15. Bb1 ({
If White would play something like} 15. Bh2 Bf8 {Black could gradually prepare
the queenside plan explained in the note to 14...Qd7.}) {Obviously, he allowed
me to play} 15... b5 {but his idea became clear once he played} 16. Nh2 {
His plan is to go Qd4, Ng4, maybe also Qg3, and build up an attack against my
king. The drawback of this plan is that I don't have any real weaknesses and
his knight on a3 is out of play. It is not easy to build up attack with such a
knight, but I needed to be careful since both his bishops are aiming at my
king.} Qd7 {I wanted to exploit the drawback of Nh2 - weakening of the a8-h1
diagonal - by preparing Bb7-Qc6 battery to attack g2-pawn.} ({I could also play
} 16... Ncd5 17. Bd2 Qb6 18. Ng4 Rac8 {but I was concerned that White can
maybe sacrifice on h6 at some point, so I wasn't sure.}) 17. axb5 axb5 18. Qd3
Qc6 19. f3 {[#] White thought that he would build up a strong attack with Ng4
next. What would you play with Black here?} (19. Qg3 {is not good because of}
Nh5) 19... h5 {I decided to prevent the attack directly by taking control of
g4-square, while also preventing any sacrifices on h6.} (19... Ncd5 {looks
like the most natural move, but after} 20. Bd2 {the b-pawn is hanging and if I
go} Ba6 {White can fix the queenside with} 21. b4 {and somehow White can
attack on the kingside more easily because my pieces are a bit stuck.}) {
Of course, every move in chess has a strong and weak side, and in this case
White exploited the weak side of 19...h5 with} 20. Bg5 {Still, I thought that
after} g6 {Black has a solid position since both of his knights are very far
from the critical square g6.} 21. Nf1 {[#] White position looks somewhat
strange with pawns on h3 and f3, knight on a3...but on the other hand, it has
no weaknesses. Still, I decided that it is time to play for maybe more than
simple equality. What would you play with Black here?} e5 {I felt like I can
exploit disharmony in white camp with this move, while also securing a good
square for the c7-knight (e6). However, it is psychologically difficult to
make such a decision because it was a maneuvering game up to this point and we
suddenly open up the position. Still, I felt that it was a good moment for it.}
({There are a few other possibilities. For example} 21... Nfd5 {but I thought
that after something simple like} 22. Qd2 {White can bring the knight to e4
via g3, or Nc2-e3 maybe; my king also becomes a bit isolated once I remove the
knight from f6.}) 22. Ba2 {The move that I was afraid of the most. With 21...
e5, I have weakened the a2-g8 diagonal and Qxg6 is a threat.} ({White cannot
take the pawn} 22. dxe5 dxe5 23. Rxe5 $2 {because of} Bc5+) ({If White plays
something like} 22. Qd2 {then I can already activate my knight via} Ne6 23. Bh4
Nd7 ({or even} 23... Nf4 $5)) 22... e4 {I decided to sharpen the game even
further. This required deep calculation, though.} ({In case of} 22... Nfd5 {
White could make some exchanges} 23. Bxd5 Qxd5 24. Bxe7 Rxe7 25. Ne3 Qc6 26.
Qd2 $14 {and get a pleasant game on the dark-squares. He could go Nc2-b4 next,
while Bb7 is limited well by the pawn on f3.}) 23. fxe4 Nxe4 24. Bxe7 ({
Intermediate move} 24. d5 {looks dangerous, but does not work because of} Qb6+
25. Be3 Nc5 26. Qd2 Bh4) 24... Rxe7 {The upside of the e4-thrust is that we
have reopened the long diagonal, so after something like Kg7, we may already
threaten a discovered attack on g2 with the knight. Also, the knight on e4 is
dominant. Therefore, White tried to exchange it with} 25. Ng3 d5 {This move
may seem positionally dubious as we block our bishop on b7, but it is more
important to create a stronghold on e4. At the same time, we are killing
White's attack and already preparing to take initiative with Qd6, Rae8, etc.}
26. Nxe4 (26. Nc2 h4 27. Nb4 Qd6 (27... Qe6 28. Nf1 Na6) 28. Nxe4 dxe4 29. Qe3
Rxa2 30. Nxa2 Nd5 31. Qg5 e3 $19) 26... dxe4 27. Qg3 Kg7 {A prophylactic move
to ensure that White never has Qxg6 ideas. We can safely say that Black is
better.} 28. Rc2 Qd7 29. Bb1 Ne8 ({It was already possible to start kingside
attack with} 29... f5 $1 {but I took my time to improve the knight first. It
had served me well on c7, but it was time to improve it to a better square.})
30. Rf2 Nd6 {The knight is headed to f5, preparing attack on the dark squares.
Suddenly, white king is the more exposed one.} 31. Nc2 Nf5 32. Qg5 f6 33. Qd2
Qd6 34. Ne3 Nxe3 {I decided to exchange the knights and simply push the pawns.}
({It was also possible to play} 34... Ng3 $5) 35. Qxe3 f5 {I did not see how
White can stop my plan to push f5-f4. Whenever he tries to exchange the queens
on f4, he gets a losing endgame because black pawn chain is just too strong.}
36. Ref1 Rf7 37. g4 {White decided to sharpen things up, although this is
risky decision as it exposes his king.} ({He probably had to play} 37. h4 {
to fix the pawn chain, but then Black can turn to queenside play with} Bd5 {
followed by ...b5-b4, with a clear initiative on both flanks.}) 37... hxg4 38.
hxg4 Rh8 {Now white king is more vulnerable than black king.} 39. Ba2 Rf6 40.
d5 {closing the long diagonal to prevent checkmate ideas on h1.} (40. g5 {
only helps Black} Rff8 {and I double on the h-file.}) {Black has a large
advantage, but unfortunately I misplayed it and did not win the game.} 40...
Qe5 (40... Bc8 $5) 41. d6 {A good practical decision to make things more
complicated.} Rxd6 {I was confident that I was winning with this move.} ({
However, I missed a beautiful direct tactical win} 41... fxg4 42. d7 {This
move bothered me, but simply} Qh5 {wins on the spot.}) {Here, Nabaty found a
string of strong defensive moves:} 42. Rg2 (42. gxf5 Rd3 $19 {was my intention.
}) 42... Rd3 43. Qa7 (43. Qb6 Bc8) 43... Rd7 {I thought that I am winning now,
but he still had a defense.} (43... Qc7 44. gxf5 e3 $1 {is winning, apparently,
but it was difficult to calculate everything at this point of the game.} 45.
Rxg6+ Kf8 46. Qa3+ Ke8 47. Re6+ Kd8 $19) 44. Qe3 $1 {Black still needs to show
precision.} f4 {I thought that this was a winning combination.} ({I had to play
} 44... fxg4 {in order to win.}) 45. Rxf4 Rh3 {However, White had a defense}
46. Rg3 Rxg3+ (46... Rd1+ 47. Kf2 Rh2+ 48. Rg2 Rd2+ {seems winning, but there
is} 49. Kf1 $1 $11 (49. Ke1 Rdxg2 50. Rf7+ Kg8 51. Rxb7+ Kh8) 49... Rdxg2 50.
Rf7+ Kh8 51. Rf8+ $11) 47. Qxg3 Qc5+ {I still thought that this is winning,
but to my disappointment he found:} 48. Kf1 (48. Qf2 Rd1+ 49. Kh2 Qxf2+ 50.
Rxf2 e3 51. Re2 Rd2 $19) 48... Qd6 (48... b4 49. g5 (49. Be6)) 49. Kg1 $1 {
which keeps equality.} Qb6+ 50. Rf2 Qc7 {The game finished in a draw in a
couple of moves.} 51. Qxc7 Rxc7 52. g5 Bc8 53. Rf6 e3 54. Kf1 Bg4 55. Bd5 Rd7
56. Bf3 Bxf3 57. Rxf3 Rd5 58. Rg3 Re5 59. Ke2 Kf7 60. b3 Kf8 1/2-1/2

