1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nd2 e6 6. Ngf3 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bb5
{This move is the invention of Magnus Carlsen. He won some impressive games
here. Nowadays, the popularity of this line decreases, but it remains a
dangerous weapon for White.} (8. Bd3 {Is the mainline and is discussed in the
next games.}) 8... Ne7 ({Vishi tried} 8... a6 $2 {and quickly get into trouble
after} 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Qa4 Rb8 11. Qa3 ({even stronger is} 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12.
Qa3 $16) 11... Bxg3 12. hxg3 cxd4 13. cxd4 $16 {[%cal Rf3e5,Re1g1,Rh1c1] 1-0 
(24) Carlsen,M (2840)-Anand,V (2779) Doha 2016}) 9. Bd3 $1 {It seems a bit
strange, but this is the strongest move for White. The knight on "e7" is
misplaced - not controling "e5" and not putting pressure on the "d4" pawn.} b6
{this logical developing move leads to trouble after:} (9... Nf5) (9... Ng6 {
are the alternatives, but White scores well here as well.}) 10. e4 $1 dxe4 11.
Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 {Winning an important tempo.} Rb8 $6 (12... Nd5 $1 $14 {
was better}) 13. dxc5 $1 {Remember this tactical motif. In many lines in
"London System," the "d6" bishop, is hanging.} Bxg3 14. hxg3 f5 $6 (14... Qxd1+
{this was the only way to stay in the game, but it is easy to understand why
Bosiocic didn't choose this move} 15. Kxd1 f5 16. Bd3 bxc5 17. Kc2 {the
endgame is horrible for Black}) 15. Qxd8 Rxd8 16. c6 $1 {I think this is what
the Croatian GM missed.} Nd5 (16... fxe4 17. c7 $18) 17. Bxd5 Rxd5 18. Rd1 {
Exchanging the last active piece of the opponent. The rest is a simple
technique.} Rxd1+ 19. Kxd1 Ba6 20. Ne5 Rc8 21. c4 b5 22. b4 $1 bxc4 23. a4 Rd8+
24. Kc2 Rd5 25. f4 1-0

