1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 e6 4. Nbd2 Bd6 5. Bg5 {Again, Carlsen uses his main
weapon of playing slightly unusual moves.} ({The normal continuation is} 5. Bg3
) 5... Be7 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 b6 ({Black is careless. More solid is} 7... Nbd7)
8. Qe2 Bb7 (8... Nbd7 $1 {avoids White's attacking idea.}) 9. Bxf6 $1 {Typical
the idea in this line is to exchange our dark-squared bishop for the
opponent's knight. With this move, Carlsen shows his aggressive intentions.
Black should look for counterplay in the centre and on the queenside.} (9. Ne5
$6 {is premature due to} Ne4 $1) 9... Bxf6 10. h4 $1 {This has been already
played in similar situations by Miladinovic - the "father of the London System.
" White adopts an aggressive approach to frighten his opponent and force him
to defend. Black's intuitive response would be to consolidate his kingside to
avoid any trouble. But this will inevitably lead to a situation where White
will hold the initiative and Black can only defend.} Nd7 11. Ng5 $1 (11. Bxh7+
{does not work because of} Kxh7 12. Ng5+ Kh6 13. f4 g6 14. g4 Kg7) 11... h6 {
This is the only way, but now, with the hook on h6, it is only a matter of
time for Black to get mated.} (11... g6 12. f4 c5 13. c3 $40 {î x Ndf3, h5})
12. f4 ({Much stronger was} 12. Nh7 $1 Re8 13. Nxf6+ Qxf6 (13... Nxf6 14. g4 $1
) 14. f4 c5 15. c3 cxd4 16. cxd4 Rac8 17. g4 $1 Qe7 18. g5 {, and Black is
under heavy pressure, but there is nothing to do, as the counterattack is not
effective.} e5 $6 19. fxe5 Nxe5 20. dxe5 Qxe5 21. Kf2 (21. Rh3 Qxb2 22. Nb3 $18
) 21... d4 22. e4 {, and Black doesn't have sufficient compensation.}) 12... c5
13. c3 Be7 14. g4 Nf6 15. a3 {Carlsen shows some hesitation. It was time to
start the second wave of the attack with} (15. O-O-O $1 c4 (15... b5 16. dxc5
Bxc5 17. Nb3) 16. Bc2 b5 17. Nh3 b4 18. cxb4 Bxb4 19. g5 $40) 15... Rc8 (15...
cxd4 16. exd4 Bd6 17. Qf3) 16. Qg2 Bd6 17. Ngf3 cxd4 18. cxd4 (18. Nxd4 e5 19.
fxe5 Bxe5 20. O-O-O $40) 18... Ne4 19. g5 h5 $1 {Black managed to remove the
knight and meet g5 with h5. The fight is over; Black cannot lose this anymore.}
20. Ne5 Nxd2 21. Qxd2 (21. Kxd2 g6 22. Rac1) 21... g6 {Ding Liren showed great
defensive skills and strong nerves and managed to hold the first wave of the
attack. After the imminent trade of the rooks on the c-file, White had to
agree to a draw} 1/2-1/2

