{[%evp 0,59,80,63,5,-9,44,37,79,61,68,4,43,49,30,-12,19,14,11,-26,-5,-10,7,-9,
10,2,-17,-15,-17,-43,-7,-52,-25,-23,-36,-47,-9,-20,-38,-26,13,10,76,6,187,-38,
72,-55,209,263,255,184,275,308,233,360,313,305,833,973,1970,29990] In the
following game we will see a model attack by GM Gata Kamsky. He employs the
interesting 9.Qe2. You will learn how to build an attack when the centre is
already closed.} 1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 e6 6. c3 Bd6
7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3 b6 9. Qe2 $5 {One of the possible plans for White. He is
preparing "e3-e4" and in the meantime preparing Rd1 and keeping the rook on
"h1".} Bb7 10. Rd1 $5 {White is keeping the tension. As we know, in this
structure, Bxg3 is always suspicious with the rook still on "h1". White is
ready to open the game now.} Re8 {I don't like this move, although it looks
logical. 10...Ne7 looks more natural to me.} 11. e4 Be7 $1 {this is a typical
way to meet "e3-e4", but I believe that White is just better after:} 12. e5 Nh5
13. a3 $1 {Takes the b4-square from the black pieces. Kamsky wants to leave
his king in the centre for a while to prevent Black from taking on g3.} c4 {
Wrong positional decision. With a closed centre it will be much harder for
Black to create any serious counterplay. In the meantime, White can slowly
prepare his attack on the kingside when Black's queenside activity looks slow
and pointless.} 14. Bb1 g6 15. Nf1 ({The thematic idea in such positions is:} 
15. Qe3 $5 b5 16. h4 $16 {[%cal Rg3h2,Rg2g4]}) 15... b5 16. Ne3 a5 {A
well-known rule is that the attack against the king is always more efficient
than the attack against an empty flang.} 17. Ng4 b4 18. Qe3 {As you can see,
Kamsky doesn't care about the queenside.} bxc3 19. bxc3 Rb8 20. Bf4 $1 {
The bishop breaks free. Despite the closed nature of the position, Kamsky
manages to activate his pieces.} ({the computer prefers} 20. Nh6+ Kg7 21. h4
Bxa3 22. Bh2 $18 {[%cal Rg2g4]}) 20... Bc8 21. Bg5 {After the exchange of the
dark-squared bishops Black will have a hard time defending all the holes
around his king.} Rb3 (21... f6 {was the most stubborn defense, but White is
still winning after:} 22. exf6 Nxf6 23. Nge5 $16) 22. h4 Qb6 23. Bc2 Rxa3 {
Winning a pawn.} 24. Bxe7 Nxe7 25. Qh6 $1 $18 {Too many pieces are attacking
"poor" Black king.} Nf5 26. Bxf5 exf5 27. Ng5 $1 {The attack is decisive.} Nf6
{Nice defense by Goganov, but Kamsky's reply was very beatiful} 28. Ne3 $1 f4
29. Nxd5 Qd8 30. O-O $1 {The beauty of chess. Castling on the move 30 and
forcing resignation is not something that you see every day. Great win by
Kamsky} 1-0

