{[%evp 0,65,39,25,25,22,22,25,27,27,65,-5,9,13,10,10,11,1,23,-19,-4,-32,-16,10,
10,-54,-26,-43,-36,-40,-53,-48,-22,-16,-20,49,64,74,74,113,113,124,118,115,115,
119,119,120,155,155,136,69,159,127,59,70,64,150,129,129,126,153,159,123,123,
111,156,169] Another attacking model game in the variation with 7.Bg3 and 8.
Bd3. In this example, we will see how Black is punished after making one slow
move in the opening. I recommend for all readers to check the games of GM
Sedlak. He played "London System" all his life and has many impressive wins
with it.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 e6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bg3
O-O 8. Bd3 b6 9. Ne5 {The other attacking idea in this structure is to occupy
the "e5" square with the knight and then start acting on the kingside.} Bb7 10.
f4 Rc8 $2 {Black is losing an important tempo. After this move, White can
easily build his attack.} ({As we know from the lecture of GM Grigorov, the
best plan in this position is} 10... Ne7 11. Qf3 Nf5 {[%cal Rd6e7,Rf5d6,Rf6e4]
I will not discuss this idea any further because it is very well explained in
the other lecture.}) 11. Bh4 Be7 ({it is too late for} 11... Ne7 12. Bxf6 gxf6
13. Qh5 f5 $2 (13... Ng6 14. Ndf3 $1 {I think Black is just lost here. White's
knight is untouchable due to Ng5. White can calmly finish the development by
castling, then Ng4 followed by f4-f5.}) 14. g4 $1 $18) 12. Bxf6 $1 {I hope
that you remember this idea from Carlsen - Ding Lieren game.} Bxf6 13. Ndf3 {
Now when there is no knight to come to "e4", White can simply bring all his
pieces to the kingside.} Be7 14. h4 $1 {Alfa-Zero style. Another idea that is
worth remembering. In this system, White's king is feeling well in the centre.}
Nxe5 (14... f6 $2 {is not possible} 15. Ng5 $3 $18) 15. Nxe5 f5 {We can
understand Brkic's desire to close the diagonal, but this move is a mistake
here. Another point to remember is that "f7-f5" is always met by "g2-g4". Then
White can open the "g" file in an appropriate moment with a decisive effect.}
16. g4 cxd4 {This exchange usually helps White} 17. exd4 Bxh4+ {Suicidal move.
Black opens another file against his king} 18. Kd2 Bf6 19. gxf5 Bxe5 20. fxe5
Qg5+ 21. Kc2 exf5 22. Qf3 {[%cal Ra1g1] Game over. The rest of the game looks
spectacular but is just good grandmaster technique.} g6 23. Rag1 Qe7 24. Bxf5
Qf7 25. Rh5 Kh8 26. Rxg6 (26. e6 $1 $18 {wins faster}) 26... Qxg6 27. Bxg6 Rxf3
28. Rxh7+ Kg8 29. Rxb7 {Probably it looks that Black has some practical
chances, but this is just an optical illusion. Black is hopeless in this
position.} Rc6 30. Be8 Rf2+ 31. Kb3 Rh6 32. Ka3 Rhh2 33. Bc6 1-0

