{[%evp 0,33,19,31,19,14,26,32,24,-52,33,26,30,15,21,19,25,27,29,25,29,21,14,23,
24,13,38,14,79,84,86,77,182,129,142,137] In the following game I will
illustrate you some typical tactics that you need to remember in this
structure. I leave the important strategical moments with brief comments
because GM Grigorov analyzes this position in his lecture.} 1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 (2.
c4 c6 3. Bf4 {It would be great that this works, but unfortunately for White
after:} dxc4 $1 {Black is better.}) 2... Nf6 3. e3 Bf5 4. c4 c6 5. Nc3 (5. Qb3
{Is another possible move order.} Qb6 6. Nc3 {Leading to the position in the
game.} (6. c5 $6 {Is not very strong here due to:} Qxb3 7. axb3 Bxb1 $1 8. Rxb1
Nbd7 9. b4 a6 10. Ra1 Rc8 {Black is just in time to solve all his problems.}))
5... e6 {This setup is not very good for Black. Nowadays, top players avoid
this structure. However, this position remains very popular at a club level
and is very important for understanding the London System.} 6. Qb3 Qb6 (6...
Qc8 $6 {Is just bad, White has an advantage after the simple:} 7. Rc1 $16) (
6... b6 $6 {Is also not very good} 7. Nf3 Be7 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O Nbd7 {The rule
is that we are waiting for Nbd7 and then:} 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. Ba6 $16) 7. c5
Qxb3 8. axb3 Nbd7 9. h3 (9. b4 {The theory considers this not the most
accurate move order, but I think White is still better here. Critical is} Nh5
10. Bc7 $1 {Typical idea which is worth remembering} (10. b5 $6 Nxf4 11. exf4
Be7 12. bxc6 bxc6 13. Ba6 Rb8 {Black is fine here, because of the counterplay
on the b-file.}) 10... Rc8 (10... Be7 11. b5) 11. Be5 $1 (11. Rxa7 $5 {Another
tricky idea} Rxc7 12. Ra8+ Ke7 13. b5 b6 (13... cxb5 14. Nxb5 Rc6 15. Nf3 $13)
14. bxc6 Rxc6 15. Ra7 (15. Bb5 {is more to the point} Rc7 16. c6 Ndf6 17. f3 g6
18. Nge2 (18. g4 $6 {is premature} Bxg4 19. fxg4 Nxg4 $15) 18... Ng7 19. Kd2 h5
20. Rha1 Nge8 21. R1a7 Rxa7 22. Rxa7+ Kd8 23. Ra8+ Ke7 $11 {The engine manages
to survive with Black, but in a practical game, I think that Black can easily
go wrong in the complications.}) 15... Nhf6 (15... Kd8 $1 16. b4 Rc7 17. Ra8+
Rc8 18. Rxc8+ Kxc8 19. Ba6+ {White still has compensation, but probably it is
not enough for the piece.}) 16. Bb5 (16. Nf3) 16... Rc8 17. c6 g6 18. Nf3 Bg7
19. cxd7 Ra8 20. d8=Q+ Kxd8 21. Rxa8+ {1-0 (21) Rusev,K (2543)-Mitkov,M (2398)
Sunny Beach 2010}) 11... Nxe5 (11... f6 12. Bd6 Bxd6 13. cxd6 a6 14. Be2 $18)
12. dxe5 a6 13. f3 $18 {Black is losing a piece}) 9... a6 10. b4 Rc8 {Black is
just in time to play this move. Now b4-b5 is not possible.} 11. Nf3 {[%cal
Rf3d2,Rd2b3,Rb3a5] White is changing the plan here.} Be7 12. Nd2 Bd8 13. Nb3 {
and If} Bc7 14. Bxc7 Rxc7 15. b5 $1 cxb5 (15... O-O 16. b6 $1 (16. bxa6 $6 {
Taking the pawn is too modest and allows Black to start counterplay on the
b-file after:} bxa6 17. Bxa6 Rb8) 16... Rcc8 17. Na5 Rb8 18. Bxa6 bxa6 19. Nxc6
Rb7 20. Rxa6 {And White's pawns are much stronger than Black's extra piece.})
16. Nxb5 $1 axb5 (16... Rc6 17. Na5 axb5 18. Nxc6 bxc6 19. Ra8+ $18) 17. Ra8+ {
1-0 (32) Osborne,M (2185)-Houska,J (2391) London 2015} *

