{In this game I will show you the famous "Jobava System"} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5
3. Bf4 {The Jobava System - The knight on "c3" is more active than on "d2",
but the drawback is that the "c" pawn is blocked. The system is suspicious
from a strategical point of view.} a6 (3... e6 4. Nb5 Na6 {is the main line})
4. e3 e6 5. g4 {White shows his aggressive intentions.} Bb4 6. Nge2 {a
critical move. White doesn't allow doubling the pawns after Bxc3} c5 $2 (6...
O-O 7. a3 Be7 8. Ng3 (8. g5 $1 Nh5 9. h4 c5 (9... Nxf4 {was stronger} 10. Nxf4
c5 {Here, the engine found a nice variation which ended in a perpetual} 11. Bd3
c4 12. Bxh7+ $5 Kxh7 13. Qh5+ Kg8 14. g6 fxg6 15. Nxg6 Rf5 16. Qh8+ Kf7 17. Qh7
Nc6 18. Rg1 Qg8 19. Nh8+ Kf8 20. Ng6+ $11) 10. Bxb8 (10. Bh2 $1 {Keeping the
bishop leaves Black with a horrible knight on h5.}) 10... Rxb8 11. dxc5 Bxc5
12. Nd4 Bxd4 (12... g6 {was necessary, and Black's position is stable.}) 13.
Qxd4 g6 14. Be2 Ng7 15. O-O-O $18 {And White's attack was successful 1-0 (44)
Carlsen,M (2876) -Sjugirov,S (2662) chess24.com INT 2020}) 8... c5 9. g5 Nfd7
10. Qh5 Re8 11. h4 Nc6 12. O-O-O b5 {And Black's attack was faster in 0-1 (26)
Artemiev,V (2708) -Giri,A (2764) Chess.com INT 2020}) 7. a3 {The Bishop on b4
is required to defend c5, so retreating would allow White to capture on c5.}
cxd4 8. axb4 dxc3 9. Nxc3 {White is already much better here. He has bishop
pair, control of the center, and chances for a kingside attack.} O-O 10. g5
Nfd7 11. h4 $1 {Similar to Sicilian defense. White starts his pawn storm on
the kingside.} Nb6 {This move doesn't help, but it is hard to suggest
something better at that point.} 12. Bd3 Nc6 13. Qh5 $1 {an important idea to
remember. White is provoking further weaknesses on Black's camp} g6 14. Qh6 e5
{Black's counterplay is late} 15. h5 Qe7 16. hxg6 fxg6 17. Bxg6 $1 Bf5 (17...
hxg6 18. Bxe5 $1 Nxe5 (18... Qxe5 19. Qh7#) 19. Qh8+ Kf7 20. Rh7+ $18 Ke8 21.
Rxe7+ Kxe7 22. Qxe5+ $18) 18. Bxf5 Rxf5 19. Bg3 {The game is practically over.
White is a pawn up and with a nice attack.} Rd8 20. g6 Rd7 21. O-O-O Qg7 22.
gxh7+ {White just transposes to a winning endgame. The rest of the game is not
so interesting} Qxh7 23. Qxh7+ Rxh7 24. Rxh7 Kxh7 25. Nxd5 Nxd5 26. Rxd5 Kg6
27. b5 axb5 28. Rxb5 Rf7 29. Bxe5 Rxf2 30. Bf4 Nd8 31. Bc7 Ne6 32. Rxb7 Rf1+
33. Kd2 Rf2+ 34. Kd1 Nc5 35. Rb6+ Kf7 36. Bf4 Ne4 37. Rb4 *

