1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 {Tricky position. Black can easily go
wrong here.} cxd4 (4... Nc6 $4 5. Nb5 $18) (4... e6 5. Nb5 Na6 $16 {The knight
is misplaced there. The difference with the 3...e6 system is that Black can't
challenge White's knight with c7-c6}) (4... a6 5. dxc5 e6 6. Na4 Bxc5 7. Nxc5
Qa5+ 8. c3 Qxc5 $16) 5. exd4 (5. Nb5 Qa5+ 6. c3 dxc3 7. Nc7+ Kd8 8. b4 Qxb4 9.
Nxa8 c2+ 10. Qd2 e5 $1 11. Bxe5 Nc6 12. Bc3 Qb1+ 13. Qc1 Bf5 {And my engine
says that White can resign.}) 5... a6 {Program move for Black.} 6. Bd3 (6. h3 {
1-0 (44) Milanovic,D (2469)-Wagner,D (2575) Berlin 2015}) (6. Nf3 Bg4 {1-0 (83)
Nakamura,H (2767)-Giri,A (2776) London 2014}) 6... Nc6 7. Nge2 {White wants to
answer Bg4 with f2-f3.} (7. Nf3 Bg4 {this pin is always unpleasant for White
in such structures}) 7... e6 8. Qd2 b5 9. O-O (9. Bxb5 $2 {doesn't work} axb5
10. Nxb5 Ne4 $19) 9... Be7 (9... Bd6 {was the safest approach} 10. Bxd6 Qxd6
$11) 10. a3 Bd7 11. h3 O-O 12. Rfe1 (12. Nd1 Na5 13. Ne3 Nc4 $11) 12... Na5 13.
Rad1 Qb6 14. Ng3 {White has nothing after the opening, but here is the
interesting part of the game. Ruslan underestimates White's attacking chances
and was crushed just for few moves.} Rfc8 $2 (14... Rfe8 15. Qc1 Nc4 $11 {
was the safest continuation for Black}) 15. Nf5 $1 exf5 (15... Bf8 16. Nh6+ $1
gxh6 17. Bxh6 $18) 16. Rxe7 Be6 $6 (16... Qd8 $5 17. Re5 $1 Ne4 18. Bxe4 dxe4
19. Rc5 Nb7 $13) 17. Bh6 $3 {Black is already lost here. In the following
analysis, I am showing you some illustrative variations} gxh6 (17... Nh5 $1 {
was the most stubborn defence} 18. Qg5 Nc6 19. Rxe6 fxe6 20. Be2 $18) (17...
Ne8 18. Rxe8+ Rxe8 19. Qg5 $18) (17... g6 18. Qg5 $18) (17... Nc6 18. Bxg7 $1
$18) (17... Kf8 18. Bxg7+ Kxe7 19. Bxf6+ Kd7 (19... Kxf6 20. Qh6+ Ke7 21. Nxd5+
$18) 20. Re1 $18) (17... Qd8 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 (18... Nh5 19. Bf6 f4 20. Rxe6 Nxf6
21. Re5 $18) 19. Qg5+ Kf8 20. Qxf6 Nc6 21. Rxe6 $18) 18. Qxh6 Rxc3 (18... Ne8
19. Bxf5 Bxf5 20. Qxb6 $18) 19. Qg5+ $1 Kf8 20. Qxf6 Rxd3 21. cxd3 {An
impressive game} 1-0

