{It is time to move to another structure.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 b6 {
Very interesting system. To learn more about it, I suggest you check Boris
Gelfand's games.} 4. e3 Bb7 5. c4 {Not the main continuation here, but a very
tricky one. I also tried it in several games with good results.} c5 {Black's
idea is logical. It seems that White can't play d4-d5 because he is losing a
pawn.} (5... Bb4+ $1 {is the main move in this position.} 6. Nfd2 $1 {Is an
important move to remember. White is planning to continue with a2-a3 followed
by Nc3} ({If} 6. Nbd2 {then the knight is misplaced and Black will simply
retreat his bishop to "e7". It is a playable line, but not a very ambitious
one.})) {Nevertheless} 6. d5 $1 {is the strongest move in the position. If
Black didn't take then White achieved a favorable version of Benoni with a
"bad" bishop on "b7"} exd5 7. Nc3 $1 {This is an idea which I saw for the
first time.} ({The "automatic"} 7. cxd5 {doesn't equalize for White after the
simple} Nxd5 $15) 7... dxc4 8. Bxc4 d5 $2 ({The strongest defense is} 8... Be7
{but even after the modest} 9. Qe2 O-O 10. e4 {White has more than enough
compensation for the sacrificing pawn. Still both 0-0 and 0-0-0 are possible,
and e4-e5 is coming soon.}) 9. Nb5 (9. Qa4+ Nbd7 10. Nb5 Bc6 11. Qc2 Rc8 12.
Be2 Bxb5 13. Bxb5 $13) 9... dxc4 10. Nc7+ Ke7 11. Qa4 Qd7 $4 (11... Ne8 12. Rd1
Qc8 13. Nxe8 Qc6) (11... Na6 12. Rd1 Nxc7 13. Rxd8 Kxd8 14. Ng5) 12. Qxc4 Bxf3
$4 (12... Bd5 13. Qc3 Na6 (13... Nc6 14. Nxa8 Ne4 15. Qa3 $1 Nb4 16. O-O-O $1
$16) 14. Nxa6 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Nd5) 13. gxf3 Qc6 14. O-O-O Nbd7 15. Rd6 Qxf3 16.
Rhd1 Rc8 17. Re6+ Kd8 18. Rxd7+ Kxd7 19. Qb5+ 1-0

