1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 c5 5. c3 Nc6 6. Nbd2 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3
b6 9. e4 $5 {Interesting continuation. It is well known that Black should
always meet e3-e4 with ...Be7, but this was a blitz game, and the Nurgyul
forgot about this rule and was crushed} dxe4 $2 {This move looks very logical
but leads to a tough position.} (9... Be7 $1) 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 (10... Bxg3 11.
hxg3 {[%cal Rh1h7,Rd3h7] Black is in big trouble here}) 11. Bxe4 Bb7 12. dxc5
Bxc5 ({The problem for Black is that} 12... bxc5 $4 {is not possible} 13. Qxd6
$18) (12... Bxg3 $2 13. hxg3 Qxd1+ 14. Rxd1 f5 15. Bxc6 Bxc6 16. Ne5 $1 $18 {
It is time for Black to resign}) 13. Qa4 $3 {This is a very nice maneuver.
White is attacking the knight, but the main idea is to transfer the queen to
the kingside and prepare Rd1} Rc8 (13... Qc8 $4 {is losing immediately} 14.
Bxh7+ Kxh7 15. Qh4+ Kg8 16. Ng5 Re8 17. Qh7+ Kf8 18. Qh8+ Ke7 19. Qxg7 $18 {
1-0 (27) Demchenko,A (2632)-Tsvetkov,A (2395) Chess.com INT 2020}) 14. Rd1 Qe8
{This move loses on a spot} (14... Qe7 $1 15. b4 $6 (15. O-O $1 {is better for
White}) 15... f5 $1 {The only defence} 16. Bd3 Nxb4 17. cxb4 Bxb4+ 18. Kf1 Rc3
$13 {[%cal Rf8d8,Rc3a3] and the computer is trying to prove to me that Black
has enough compensation. Optically it doesn't seem so, but I can't argue with
the machine.}) 15. Bxh7+ Kxh7 16. Qh4+ Kg6 17. Qg5+ Kh7 18. Qh5+ Kg8 19. Ng5 {
and mate} 1-0

