{[%evp 0,61,31,26,13,26,24,24,34,14,37,37,21,21,19,0,21,-7,32,2,31,3,-1,-8,-27,
-22,-18,124,129,144,86,96,16,89,89,69,89,118,129,121,182,175,175,270,270,270,
224,224,106,629,811,813,859,964,964,939,833,869,869,861,861,858,858,651]} 1. d4
Nf6 2. Bf4 d5 3. e3 e6 4. Nd2 c5 5. c3 Nc6 6. Ngf3 Bd6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3 Qe7 (
8... Qc7 {doesn't work with the knight on "c6" because of:} 9. dxc5 Bxg3 10.
hxg3 $16 {White has a pawn up and an attack}) 9. Ne5 {As we know we should
allow e6-e5} Nd7 10. Nxd7 Bxd7 $2 {My survey wasn't be complete without
showing you the most famous trap in London System} (10... Qxd7 11. Bxd6 Qxd6
12. dxc5 Qxc5 13. Bxh7+ {With a bishop on "c8" this leads only to a draw.} Kxh7
14. Qh5+ Kg8 15. Ne4 g6 16. Qg5 Qe7 17. Nf6+ Kg7 18. Nh5+ Kg8 $11) 11. Bxd6
Qxd6 12. dxc5 Qxc5 (12... Qe7 {Leaves Black in the game, but White is just
with an extra pawn after the simple:} 13. b4 (13. O-O {could be even stronger,
because the pawn is still untouchable.})) 13. Bxh7+ $1 {Out of nowhere this
tactic simply works here.} Kxh7 14. Qh5+ Kg8 15. Ne4 $1 {Thanks to undefended
Black's queen White transfers the knight with tempo.} Qc4 (15... g6 {we can
see the difference between 10...Bxd7 and 10...Qd7 in this line.} 16. Nxc5 gxh5
17. Nxd7 Rfd8 18. Nf6+ Kf8 19. Nxh5 $18 {With two extra pawns, White's win is
out of question.}) 16. Ng5 Rfd8 (16... Qd3 17. e4 $18 {the only move, but good
enough}) 17. Qxf7+ Kh8 18. Qh5+ Kg8 19. Rd1 {Shankland didn't resign and
survive few more moves, but he could just stop the clock here.} e5 20. Qf7+ Kh8
21. e4 Ne7 22. Qxe7 Bb5 23. Rd2 Qxa2 24. Qf7 Qa1+ 25. Rd1 Qxb2 26. Qh5+ Kg8 27.
Qh7+ Kf8 28. Qh8+ Ke7 29. Qxg7+ Kd6 30. Rxd5+ Kc6 31. Qf6+ 1-0

